<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Irish PM Haughey Under Cash Inquiry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Former Irish Prime Minister
Charles Haughey has been formally named as a recipient of more
than a million pounds when an official investigation into cash
payments to politicians opened in Dublin early today.
</P>
<P>
Dennis McCullough, counsel for the tribunal, told the tribunal
today that Haughey, who had been Irish prime minister between 1979
and 1992, received 1.3 million pounds (about 2 million U.S.
dollars) from businessman Ben Dunne between 1987 and 1991, said
reports from Dublin.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Michael Lowry, a promising figure in the ruling Fine
Gael party of Prime Minister John Bruton, resigned when a
newspaper report said that Dunne had paid for the renovation of
his house.
</P>
<P>
McCullough told the tribunal that Haughey had approached Dunne
to "help him out of financial difficulty" and that four separate
payments were made through intermediaries to the former prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
"The evidence which Mr Dunne will give is that between December
1987 and November 1991 he arranged for 1.3 million pounds (about 2
million dollars) to be paid to the benefit of Charles J. Haughey,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
McCullough said that there was no suggestion that money paid to
either Haughey or Lowry or any other figures to be named in the
investigation was intended to buy political favors.
</P>
<P>
However, the news that a millionaire Irish businessman had
given cash to some politicians has raised calls for a new code
governing funding of political parties and more transparency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
