<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Launches Campaign to Invite Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Egypt is to launch seminars on
investment in the country in three European cities in May as the
latest push to invite foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
A team of Egyptian businessmen and investors will take part,
said today Executive Chairman of the General Investment Authority
Ibrahim Fawzi, who will be at the helm of the delegation to the
three cities.
</P>
<P>
Fawzi said the first two seminars, to open in the Spanish city
of Barcelona on May 19 and Madrid on May 20, will tackle the
prospects for investment and privatization in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The third seminar, to be held in the Norwegian capital Oslo on
May 23, is expected to attract some 125 Norwegian firms to deal
with Egypt, he added.
</P>
<P>
While the European businessmen will be briefed on the
investment atmosphere and facilities in Egypt. Egyptian investors
will hold intensive talks with their Spanish and Norwegian
counterparts to discuss setting up joint ventures, Fawzi said.
</P>
<P>
The move followed a series of measures to lure foreign
investment in a campaign to revitalize the country's economy and
create jobs.
</P>
<P>
The government has set up a task force of Egyptian businessmen
abroad to convince foreign investors to put their money into
Egypt, and announced new legislation on investment guarantees and
tax exemptions.
</P>
<P>
A new bill approved by the parliament last month bans all
threats to private enterprise, such as seizures, nationalization
and sequestration.
</P>
<P>
The government also plans to offer 20-year tax holidays for all
investment in the New Valley under a project launched by President
Hosni Mubarak to boost economic activity in the south-western
desert region.
</P>
<P>
The government of Prime Minister Kamal Al-Ganzouri has made
boosting investment its top priority since coming to power in
January 1996 and has vowed to remove all obstacles to that goal.
</P>
<P>
According to the International Monetary Fund, foreign
investment in Egypt is expected to reach 2.1 billion U.S. dollars
in 1997 from 650 million last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
