<HEADLINE> US Threatens to Respond to Iraqi Helicopter Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The United States today
threatened to respond if Iraq flies helicopters to pick up Muslim
pilgrims from Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has announced that it would send helicopters to pick up
"sick and exhausted" Muslim pilgrims from Mecca, Saudi Arabia, and
the move will start today.
</P>
<P>
In reaction to Iraq's announcement, White House spokesman Mike
McCurry said, "We will respond appropriatedly."
</P>
<P>
He demanded that Iraq take another measures to bring those sick
and exhausted" Muslim pilgrims back. "There are other means and
procedures available for the transportation of... pilgrims," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"We would encourage the government of Iraq to meet its
obligations under U.N. Security Council resolutions. We will
monitor carefully any potential violations in the no-fly zone," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The United States and its allies have enforced two no-fly zones
over the northern and southern parts of Iraq since the 1991 Gulf
War, banning Iraqi aircraft flying over their own territory.
</P>
<P>
The no-fly zone in southern Iraq was expanded unilaterally by
the United States last September as a punishment on Iraq for its
sending of troops to northern Iraq at the invitation of a Kurdish
faction.
</P>
<P>
McCurry did not say what kind of response the United States
would make but said, "We're not going to shoot down civilian
helicopters." 
</P>
</TEXT>
