<HEADLINE> China to Seek Common Prosperity with Latin America: Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng said here
today that China is willing to expand its economic and trade
cooperation with Latin American countries in a bid to seek common
prosperity and development.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with visiting Uruguayan President Julio Maria
Sanguinetti this afternoon, Li said that since Sanguinetti's 1988
visit to China, great changes have taken place in both countries,
and they have made marked achievements in their bilateral
cooperation in various sectors.
</P>
<P>
The two nations have also maintained good coordination in world
affairs, Li said, expressing full confidence over the future of
their bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Since the establishment of diplomatic ties, Sanguinetti said,
bilateral relations have progressed smoothly, and cooperation in
politics, economy, and trade have also been fruitful.
</P>
<P>
At present, the world is marching toward multi-polarization,
and China's ever-rising world status is one of the symbols of this
new situation.
</P>
<P>
Uruguay emphasizes its relations with China, and there's great
potential for their economic and trade cooperation, the president
said, adding that many Uruguayan enterpreneurs are accompanying
him on his current tour, and they will play an active role in
expanding the economic and trade cooperation between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Sanguinetti briefed Li on the establishment of the "south
common market" by four Latin American countries, describing it as
an important action in compliance with the world's
multi-polarization.
</P>
<P>
Since the end of the Cold War, the world is stepping toward
multi-polarization, which is warmly welcomed by people of all
countries, Li said.
</P>
<P>
China has always maintained that domestic issues of any country
should be handled by its own people, rather than by one or two big
countries, the Premier noted.
</P>
<P>
China supports the unity and self-reliance of the Latin American
countries, and their efforts in establishing the "south common
market," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed his appreciation for Uruguay's "one China"
position over the issue of Taiwan, and its support to China over
the human rights issue.
</P>
<P>
Sanguinetti noted that to pursue the "one China" policy and
develop relations with China follows the general trend, and
Uruguay will unswervingly stick to this policy, which is also a
common understanding of the Latin American countries and people.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also briefed each other on the economic
development of their countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
