<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czech Republic Asks for Security Deposit on Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The Czech government today sought
the leverage of imposing a security deposit on foreign imports to
help reduce the country's foreign trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
Compliance with the measure, which took effect immediately
after today's announcement, is mandatory for importers to clear
the procedure at the Czech Republic's customs, the government said.
</P>
<P>
However, before making it official, Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus
indicated that the measure could be lifted at the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The security, or earnest money equivalent to 20 percent of the
value of import, is required to be deposited at designated
financial institutions, and bears no interest.
</P>
<P>
The Czech Republic has been running a huge foreign trade
deficit in recent years, and the imbalance mounted to 161 billion
Korun (about 5.3 billion U.S. dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The deficit reached 29 billion Korun (1 billion dollars) in the
first two months of this year, and was projected to total 220
billion Korun (7.6 billion dollars) for the whole year.
</P>
<P>
The country's foreign trade deficit now stands at 8.5 percent
of its gross domestic product (GDP), which is generally considered
to be alarming for maintaining the health of economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
