<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt's Law Circle Demands Containment of Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The Egyptian Society for
International Law today urged the world community to take more
serious steps to check Israel's settlement policy.
</P>
<P>
"Israel, by its settlement operations in East Jerusalem, is
breaking its pledges and the commitments made in Madrid conference
and the Oslo agreements," the organization said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"It obviously breaches the firm international rule which holds
it impermissible to annex territories by force or alter legal
situations and conditions on the ground in the occupied
territories," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Thus, it pointed out, the condemnation of Israel and the freeze
of ties should be "the least thing to be taken in this respect."
</P>
<P>
Blaming the Jewish state for the current Mideast stalemate, the
Egyptian society called on "Arab and Muslim states well as all
legitimacy-loving states to take more practicable measures to
deter the Jewish state and check its unlawful behavior and
designations."
</P>
<P>
The society, a firebrand critic of the Jewish state, also
directed criticism at the international community for lack of
counterattack against the Israeli violation of international law.
</P>
<P>
"The Israeli conduct in the United Nations and especially in the
UN Security Council testifies to the inaction of world community
in confronting Israel and its double standard dealing," it
lamented.
</P>
<P>
The UN Security Council has failed to pass a draft resolution
condemning the Israeli construction of a new Jewish neighborhood
in East Jerusalem because of the two vetoes cast by the United
States, a key sponsor of the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it pointed out that the conduct of some big powers
are "worrying" as it violates the principles on which the new
world order is to rest, in an apparent reference to the position
taken by the U.S. in favor of Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks were stalled over a month
since Israel decided on April 18 to press ahead with a Jewish
neighborhood in disputed East Jerusalem despite international
objection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
