<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea's Trade Deficit Hits 7.5 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 21 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's trade deficit reached
7.5 billion U.S. dollars in the first quarter, with exports at
29.8 billion dollars and imports at 37.2 billion dollars, the
Customs Administration said today.
</P>
<P>
Calculated on a customs-clearance basis, the red-ink figure was
up 3.3 billion dollars from the 4.2 billion dollars recorded a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
Exports marked successive decline of 8.8 percent in January,
5.1 percent in February and 3.1 percent in March, whereas imports
showed increases of 4 percent, 0.1 percent and 8.9 percent,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The nation suffered a trade deficit of 9,445 million dollars
with developed nations, up 76 million dollars from a year
earlier. Its trade surplus with developing countries fell from 4.1
billion dollars to 1.96 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Semiconductors and automobiles recorded notable drops in
exports with 40.2 percent and 11.1 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Major import items included TVs, cars, durable and non-durable
consumer goods and raw materials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
