<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Welcomes Reciprocal Visits Between Greek, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government has
welcomed reciprocal visits between Greek and Turkish Cypriots and
described them as a desirable development and a good start.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday more than 400 Turkish Cypriots crossed over to
the government-controlled southern areas of the island to pray
in one of the Muslim holiest shrines near the southern coastal
town of Larnaca.
</P>
<P>
Greek Cypriots are due to visit the Turkish-controlled
Monastery of Apostlos Andreas, on the island's most eastern tip,
in the Karpass Peninsula, to celebrate Easter Mass this Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing today, Government
Spokesman Manolis Christofides voiced welcome to such exchange of
visits, and noted that "humanitarian in nature as they may be,
they have obvious political benefits."
</P>
<P>
"We welcome such developments, this is a good start and an
example of respect of the religious beliefs of each citizen of
the Republic and for places of worship," Christofides said.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government, he said, is looking into various
other events which can boost efforts for rapprochement between
the citizens of the island country.
</P>
<P>
"One can assume that these reciprocal visits will have
beneficial results on the political effort to find a settlement
in Cyprus," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that "this is the first sign of breaking the
ice," expressing the hope that such visits will continue.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believed that the exchange of visits were the
result of the ongoing U.N.-led proximity talks between the Greek
and Turkish Cypriot sides, which began on March 10.
</P>
<P>
The talks were aimed at paving the way for the U.N. proposed
face-to-face negotiations between leaders of the two communities
and getting the two sides to adopt good-will gestures to create
a positive climate for direct negotiations.
</P>
<P>
This Eastern Mediterranean island has remained divided since
1974 when Turkish troops occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of an Athens-backed coup.
</P>
<P>
The Greek and Turkish Cypriots have been separated and are
not allowed to cross the Green Line, which is controlled by the
1,200-strong U.N. Peace-Keeping Force in Cyprus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
