<HEADLINE> Pak Government to Lay Emphasis on Local Power Plants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani government has
decided to pay special attention to the development of
hydro-electric and indigenous fuel-based thermal generation in its
forthcoming energy policy.
</P>
<P>
According to sources from the Ministry of Water and Power the
new energy policy is expected to be announced at the end of next
month.
</P>
<P>
In its new energy policy, the government is expected to focus
on the private small and medium hydel plants, which have the
advantages of environment friendliness and tolerable pressure on
balance of payments as the required machinery can be produced
locally.
</P>
<P>
Under the policy, grids, transmission lines and other
infrastructure will be extended to improve accessibility of
hydro-potential sites, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that the strategic shift in the policy would
be an emphasis on transport and communications. A significant
portion of the required transport infrastructure is linked with
the development of the thermal power plants.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the large increase in the import of fuel
will need port handling facilities, which will have to be
transported from port to power plants, necessitating investment in
roads or pipelines.
</P>
<P>
It is one of the main objectives of the policy to restore
railways' role as the main carrier of long distance bulk freight,
which is considered to be fuel-efficient, environment-friendly and
export-promoting.
</P>
<P>
In this context, foreign investment will be sought on the basis
of schemes, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
In pursuance of the power sector policy announced in March
1994, all public sector thermal power stations were to be
privatised and new ones set up only in the private sector.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
