<HEADLINE> Five Palestinians Injured By Israeli Soldiers Near </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Five Palestinian villagers were
 wounded in a clash with Israeli soldiers in the Sureif Village
near Hebron today, according to a report of JMCC, a Palestinian
press service based in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The incident took place when Israeli security forces drove
bulldozers into the village apparently preparing for demolishing
the home of Jmaal Al-Hour, a member of the Islamic Resistance
Movement (Hamas).
</P>
<P>
Palestinian protesters clashed with the soldiers. One the five
was in a critical condition after sustaining wounds in the neck
by live ammunition.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli military authorities reimposed a curfew on the
village after the clashes.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Israeli security forces located the body
of a missing soldier, Sharon Edri in the village and
discovered a Hamas cell allegedly responsible for the killing of
at least 11 and the wounding of 49 other Israelis over the
past two years.
</P>
<P>
A swarm of 400 soldiers, backed by jeeps and helicopters,
moved into the village on April 10. A curfew was also
imposed on the village. It was only lifted before the Muslim
holiday Id al-Adha on April 18.
</P>
<P>
Five people died in the village. They were unable to
receive urgent medical treatment owing to the continuous curfew
and siege.
</P>
<P>
After a lull during Id al-Adha, the Palestinians today
resumed rock and petrol bomb war against Israel in the West
Bank. Two petrol bombs were hurled at Israeli vehicles near a
settlement not far from Nablus. No one was injured in the
attack.
</P>
<P>
Similar incidents also took place Near Ramallah and
Nablus. Petrol bombs were thrown at an Israeli cars. No one was
injured, but a car was damaged by the fire. 
</P>
</TEXT>
