<HEADLINE> Foreign Investments In South Korea Rise Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Direct foreign investments in South
Korea surged 372 percent to 2.12 billion U.S. dollars in the first
quarter of 1997, the Ministry of Finance and Economy said today.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry report said the number of foreign investment
projects only increased 12 percent, which means there is a sharp
increase in the average investment amount.
</P>
<P>
The foreign investment in the first quarter has already
exceeded the total amount recorded in 1995, and accounts for 66.3
percent of the figure in 1996.
</P>
<P>
A ministry spokesman attributed the the rapid growth to the
improvement of domestic business environment, such as simplified
investment procedures and the government's financial and policy
supports to foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment in manufacturing sector stood at 907 million
U.S. dollars, increasing by 370 percent as compared with previous
year.
</P>
<P>
Investment in non-manufacturing sector recorded an even bigger
year-on-year gain of 373.5 percent to 1.2 billion U.S. dollars, up
from 257 million U.S. dollars in the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. investors increased their investment in South Korea by
791.5 percent compared with the corresponding period of 1996 while
European companies recorded a 205 percent increase. 
</P>
</TEXT>
