<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Officials on US Court Order on Long Beach Port Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- China Ocean Shipping (Group)
Company (COSCO) will reserve its right to ask for compensation for
losses caused by a US court order to cancel its lease agreement
with the Port of Long Beach in the US.
</P>
<P>
COSCO officials made the announcement here today in an
interview with a group of local journalists.
</P>
<P>
The COSCO American Incorp., an overseas branch of the leading
Chinese ocean shipping firm, signed an agreement with the US
harbor on November 15, 1995, to rent an abandoned US Navy port in
the city of Long Beach, according to the officials.
</P>
<P>
They said the deal was signed in accordance with US law, and
and the court decision may result in heavy financial loss to the
company. COSCO has invested 36.1 million US dollars to buy six
cranes in the port, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
The US court has demanded that the Port of Long Beach cancel
the agreement due to the project's negative influence on national
security and on environment and cultural relics.
</P>
<P>
Beverly O'Neill, Mayor of the City of Long Beach, and George
M. Murchison, President of the Board of the Harbor Commissioners
of the Port of Long Beach, who are visiting Beijing, also were
interviewed by the Chinese reporters today.
</P>
<P>
In her speech, the Mayor called COSCO a "very valued customer"
and "part of the Port of Long Beach."
</P>
<P>
Murchison said that the port would accept the court order to
cancel the agreement. As for the cause of the problem, he said,
"state process conflicts with federal process" over the issue.
</P>
<P>
Murchison insisted that both sides will suffer financially from
the decree. But he admitted that so far, the properties of the
former US Navy port have not been transferred to the Port of Long
Beach. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
