<DOCNO> XIE19970422.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Left Parties Set Up Alliance Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 21 (Xinhua) -- France's leftwing parties reached
an agreement today to present their common candidates in the
constituencies where the extreme-right National Front (FN) party
is active, in the early legislative elections to be held in about
one month's time.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the Socialist Party, the Communist Party and
other leftwing parties and the Green Party made the decision at a
meeting today at the headquarters of the Mouvement des Citoyens
party headed by former Defense Minister Jean-Pierre Chevenement.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac will announce this evening his
decision to dissolve the National Assembly (lower house of
parliament) and to organize early legislative elections on May 25
and June 1.
</P>
<P>
National Secretary of the Communist Party Robert Hue said that
the leftwing parties will present their common candidates for
parliament in fewer than a dozen constituencies.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, First Secretary of the French Socialist Party Lionel
Jospin will have a meeting with Hue on April 28 to decide on a
common program for the two main leftwing parties in the elections.
</P>
<P>
Socialist and Communist party officials said that the two
parties have overcome their difference on European Monetary Union,
after Jospin said Sunday that he would reject the European single
currency if it resulted in more austerity socio-economic measures
in France.
</P>
<P>
Hue, who has vowed to fight for an overall rejection of the
monetary union, described Jospin's speech as "a positive
evolution."
</P>
<P>
An opinion poll conducted by the daily Le Figaro and the SOFRES
polling institute said today that the ruling right-center majority
will lose about 150 parliament seats in the elections, but will
keep an absolute majority. 
