<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Business Confidence Advances, Conference Board Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Confidence among the U.S.'s
business leaders rose during the first quarter of 1997, according
to a research group here today.
</P>
<P>
The New York based Conference Board reported that its Measure
of Business Confidence increased to 57 in the first quarter, up
from 54 during the final quarter of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The index is based on quarterly surveys of more than 150 chief
executive officers and other business leaders representing a wide
variety of industries.
</P>
<P>
Forty-seven percent say the economy has improved over the last
six months, up from less than 45 percent in the last quarter of
1996. Business leaders also are marginally more positive about
business conditions in their own industries. More than 45 percent
say conditions are better than they were six months ago, up
slightly from the last quarter. Those saying conditions are worse
fell slightly to about 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
Among the various industries surveyed, chief executives in
wholesale and retail trade reported the largest improvement in
business conditions. Business leaders in banking and finance,
however, reported a deterioration in business conditions.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 percent of the chief executives plan to hire
additional workers during the coming year -- up substantially from
the 10 percent figure of a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Business leaders say wage and salary costs, and other employee
benefits, are not major obstacles to hiring more workers this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
