<HEADLINE> Peaceful Reunification Irreversible: Scholars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- A group of scholars and experts
said today in Beijing that the question of Taiwan will surely be
solved, and the ultimate reunification of the motherland is an
irreversible trend.
</P>
<P>
They made the pronouncement at a symposium held by the Hong
Kong-based newspaper "Wen Wei Po" to discuss the current situation
and future prospect of the cross-strait relations.
</P>
<P>
They noted that after the resolution of the questions of Hong
Kong and Macao, the question of Taiwan will be solved in
accordance with the basic principles of "peaceful reunification,
and one country, two systems" and the eight-point propositions put
forward by President Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
They said the return of Hong Kong is a milestone in China's
reunification process, adding that the successful implementation
of the "one country, two systems" concept will set an example for
the resolution of the Taiwan question, as well as the ultimate
reunification.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the current situation on the Taiwan Island, the
participants said the Taiwan authorities are still blocking the
exchanges between the two sides of the Taiwan Straits by creating
"two Chinas" or "one China, one Taiwan."
</P>
<P>
They urged the Taiwan authorities to return to the principle of
"one China," open the direct postal, commercial and transport
links as soon as possible, and conduct political negotiations to
end the confrontation between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Dianming, vice-president and secretary-general of the
Taiwan Studies Society, said the principle of "one China" is the
prerequisite for concluding the peaceful reunification, and any
thought of wavering or making compromises regarding Chinese
sovereignty will be futile.
</P>
<P>
Wang Sheng, an official of the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences, said political negotiation is an effective way to
improve the cross-strait relations, and the Taiwan authorities
should respond quickly to the mainland's proposals.
</P>
<P>
Wang Jianmin, a research fellow of the Chinese Academy of
Social Sciences, also commented on the importance of the direct
postal, commercial and transport links between the two sides,
saying that the two sides enjoy a vast potential in their economic
and trade relations, and the Taiwan authorities can never block
the development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
