<HEADLINE> Joint Commission Still Responsible for Angolan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Although the Angolan government
of national unity and reconciliation has taken office, the Joint
Commission Overseeing the Angolan Peace Process will still be in
charge of the remaining tasks of the Lusaka peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed here today by the United Nations special
envoy in Angola Blondin Beye, who just returned here from
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
He added that after the government of national unity and
reconciliation was sworn in on April 11 and the UNITA parliament
members took their posts in the National Assembly, both heads of
the Angolan government and UNITA delegations in the joint
commission were assigned to new posts.
</P>
<P>
However, the implementation of the peace agreement will still
be charged by the joint commission, which under the present
situation is to be reshaped, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Beye told reporters that before April 11, the implementation
of the Lusaka peace agreement was in the charge of the joint
commission under his leadership, which was made up of
representatives from the Angolan government, the UNITA, and
observers including the United States, Russia and Portugal.
</P>
</TEXT>
