<HEADLINE> Outlook of China's Tourism Good, PATA Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese mainland is predicted
to be the leading tourism destination by the year 2000, followed
by Hong Kong, Thailand, Singapore, and Malaysia, according to
the '96 Annual Report of the Pacific Asia Travel Association
(PATA).
</P>
<P>
In terms of tourism arrivals, China now ranks fourth and
Indonesia, fifth, in the region, says the annual report which was
delivered at PATA's 46th Annual Conference opened here today.
</P>
<P>
Among the biggest tourism players, China, Indonesia and
Australia have shown the strongest overall growth in the 1990s,
the report says.
</P>
<P>
As the center of the global economy moves towards the Pacific
Asia region, it is not surprising that tourism there is now
growing faster than in any other region, the report points out.
</P>
<P>
According to PATA statistics, compared with average world
tourism growth of 5.1 percent annually between 1991 and 1995, the
PATA region increased its arrivals by 9.3 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
From a 10.8 percent share of tourist arrivals from throughout
the world in 1991, PATA's figure increased by two percent to 12.7
percent in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
