<HEADLINE> African Landmine Seminar Starts in Harare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Senior officials from the the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) began a three-day
seminar to map out a strategy to rid the region of some 20
million mines which have claimed over 250,000 victims since 1961.
</P>
<P>
Organized by the International Committee of the Red Cross
(ICRC), the seminar will consider possible initiatives on the
landmines problem in southern Africa, where 10 of the 12 SADC
states have recorded casualties.
</P>
<P>
Dominique Dufour, head of the regional delegation of the ICRC,
said the solution to the landmines menace requires comprehensive
action encompassing outright ban on the use, production,
stockpiling and export of anti-personnel mines.
</P>
<P>
It should also be combined with greatly expanded programs for
enhanced mine clearance and massive increase in assistance to
victims, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to the ICRC, only some 400,000 mines have been
removed since serious clearance operations began in 1991. 
</P>
