<HEADLINE> Chinese Inland, Hong Kong to Have Enhanced Tourism Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- A top Hong Kong tourism official
predicts the tourism business will boom in both the Chinese inland
and Hong Kong after the latter's return to China on July 1.
</P>
<P>
Amy Chan, Executive Director of Hong Kong Tourist Association
(HKTA), made the remark at a press conference held here today at
the opening of the '97 Annual Conference of the Pacific Asia
Travel Association.
</P>
<P>
Chan said that tourist departments on both sides have been
working together, and will continue to do so to promote Hong Kong
and other Chinese cities as attractive tourist destinations on the
world tourist market.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong will be a complementary destination to China," she
noted, saying that inland tourism businesses can "take advantage
of Hong Kong's experience and expertise in international tourism
marketing."
</P>
<P>
Chan pointed out Hong Kong has been an important source market
for China, with nearly 29 million Hong Kong people visiting the
Chinese inland last year, while the number of inland tourists to
Hong Kong is growing rapidly.
</P>
<P>
She emphasized her confidence in Hong Kong's future, saying the
city will continue to be a cosmopolitan city with unique scenery
to entice tourists around the world.
</P>
<P>
Chan revealed HKTA is organizing a large-scale promotion to
celebrate the first 100 days of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR).
</P>
<P>
Called "100 Days of Wonders," the campaign, running from July 1
to October 8, features a wide range of offers and events, such as
festivities for the handover of Hong Kong from Britain to China,
specially-created tours, and hotel and food-related deals.
</P>
<P>
Tourists will also have the chance to win prizes valued at some
one million Hong Kong dollars in the 100 Days of Wonder Lucky
Draw, which will take place on October 22.
</P>
<P>
Tourism has been a pillar of Hong Kong's economy for
decades. Last year, the city received a record 11 million
visitors, earning tourism revenue of over 10 billion US dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
