<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac to Dissolve Parliament to Secure Launching of Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 21 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac is
expected to announce this evening the dissolution of the National
Assembly, or the lower house of parliament, and the organization
of early legislative elections in a bid to ensure France's entry
into the European Monetary Union (EMU).
</P>
<P>
The French presidential palace confirmed today that Chirac will
make a radio-television speech this evening to announce his
decision to the French people.
</P>
<P>
Chirac met Prime Minister Alain Juppe, Senate President Rene
Monory and National Assembly President Philippe Seguin this
morning in his office for consultations over the dissolution,
which is required by the French Constitution.
</P>
<P>
The dissolution will put an end to the 10th legislature of the
Fifth Republic of France, and will be the fifth dissolution of
parliament by the president of the republic since General Charles
de Gaulle did so in 1962.
</P>
<P>
Under the French Constitution, legislative elections should be
held 20 to 40 days after the president dissolves the parliament,
and the next legislative elections are widely expected to be held
on May 28 and June 1, both of which fall on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The main justification for Chirac to dissolve the parliament is
to avoid an overlap between the originally scheduled legislative
elections in April 1998 and the deadline to meet the criteria of
the Maastricht Treaty for joining the European single currency,
the Euro, on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Maastricht Treaty requires all candidates for the Euro to
cut their public deficits to below three percent of their gross
domestic product (GDP) by the end of 1997, and the European Union
will decide in the first half of 1998 which member countries are
qualified.
</P>
<P>
Despite the austere socio-economic policy adopted by the
government of Prime Minister Juppe over the past two years,
France's public deficit now stays at four percent of its GDP.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, social discontent remains unabated since last winter
and the country's unemployment rate stays at 12.8 percent, which
is greatly blamed on the policy of social and economic austerity
of the government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970422.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
