<HEADLINE> Taiwan Authorities' Diplomacy With Money Criticized (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- A signed article released today
by the Xinhua News Agency calls for all Chinese people, including
the Taiwan compatriots, to show greater contempt for the Taiwan
authorities' plot to split the motherland by practicing "dollar
diplomacy."
</P>
<P>
The article says that in recent years, the Taiwan authorities
have sought international support for the position of so-called
"independent political entities," and they have expended large
amounts of manpower, material and funds in the name of "expanding
living space internationally."
</P>
<P>
They play a farce again and again as they continue to spend
money on buying diplomatic relations with African countries; to
employ public relations companies to canvass for support in the
U.S. Congress; to send high-ranking officials abroad to promise
economic "assistance"; and to claim that one billion U.S. dollars
will buy them their ticket into the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few years, the article says, the Taiwan
authorities have spent about one million U.S. dollars to hire more
than 20 public relations firms and advisory groups to make contact
with the White House, the U.S. Congress, Wall Street and major
newspapers in the United States.
</P>
<P>
In order to help Taiwan "President" Lee Teng Hui visit the
United States, the Taiwan Research Institute, often referred to as
an "underground foreign ministry," paid Cassidy Associates 4.5
million U.S. dollars over a three-year period to go canvassing for
its operation.
</P>
<P>
Informed U.S. sources said that after staff members of the
Cassidy Associates received the money from Taiwan, they met with
U.S. Congressmen, government officials and journalists, and
pressured representatives of every state to vote for Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Peter Rosenblatt, a White House lawyer, has been hired by
Taiwan as an advisor at a monthly salary of 8,500 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The article quoted one American employed by Taiwan in a similar
position as saying, "Some people in Taiwan will knock on your door
at any time to ask you to do things for them."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970422.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Authorities' Diplomacy With Money Criticized (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At the end of October 1996, just before the US presidential
election, some mass media, including "Asia Week" of Hong Kong and
"Newsweek" and "Wall Street Journal" of the United States,
revealed that the Taiwan authorities had offered money to the US
for political purposes.
</P>
<P>
The incident once again exposed the Taiwan authorities'
notorious penchant for "dollar diplomacy," which involves such
organs as the Taiwan Research Institute and the American Institute
in Taiwan, as well as a total of more than 10 million US dollars,
the article says.
</P>
<P>
The "Los Angeles Times" quoted a former US official as saying
that "Taiwan is indeed qualified for the title of master of
illegal donations and canvassing expert."
</P>
<P>
The various actions carried out by the Taiwan authorities were
strongly opposed by the people on the island long before this, and
the revelation that Taiwan had given political donations to the US
put its policy of "dollar diplomacy" in trouble.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan's non-ruling parties and media also repeatedly
complained that the authorities believe that money is everything,
and requested them to conduct a thorough self-examination on the
existing "diplomatic" policy.
</P>
<P>
The article says the reserve of foreign exchange and the
economic strength of the Taiwan authorities have been built up by
the blood and sweat of the people of Taiwan, and that it is a sin
for the authorities to squander either the money or power wantonly.
</P>
<P>
"Dollar diplomacy" is simply an attempt to create "two Chinas,"
and an obscene way to gain "historical status" and an
"international name" for a handful of people rather than to
"expand international living space."
</P>
</TEXT>
