<HEADLINE> Chirac to Dissolve Parliament to Secure Launching of Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In order to prevent the next legislative elections from
becoming a national referendum on whether France should join the
Euro, Chirac has decided to secure a new majority in the
parliament through early elections.
</P>
<P>
This will give him a free reign -- at least for the next five
years during the term of the new legislature as well as his
presidency which ends in 2002 -- to carry through his austerity
plans aimed at meeting the budgetary criteria for joining the Euro.
</P>
<P>
It will also allow him to continue the economic and financial
structural reforms in France, "the other side of the coin" he
moulded since becaming president in May 1995.
</P>
<P>
Local press reports said the decision to dissolve parliament is
also encouraged by a recent poll by the Interior Ministry, which
showed that the ruling majority could maintain 361 seats in the
557-seat National Assembly if the elections were held now.
</P>
<P>
A poll published today by the daily Le Figaro showed that the
ruling Gaullist Rally for the Republic (RPR) and the Union for
French Democracy (UDF) will lose some 150 seats in the next
elections, but they will keep 318 seats, 40 seats more than the
278-seat absolute majority required for adopting bills.
</P>
<P>
The poll also showed that the Socialist Party of Lionel Jospin
will be the biggest, if not the only, beneficiary of the early
elections. The Socialists and their ecologist allies will win 34.5
percent of the votes in the first round, it said.
</P>
<P>
In a televised speech Sunday evening, Jospin said that if the
Maastricht Treaty criteria for joining the Euro bring about a new
"tightening up" of the French economy, his party will reject the
treaty.
</P>
<P>
He also promised that if he became the next prime minister, he
would not adopt a policy of socio-economic austerity.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, officials of the ruling majority have pointed out
that the dissolution of parliament will not bring about any major
change of policy.
</P>
<P>
The Minister of Economy and Finance Jean Arthuis said today that
France is determined to respect the Maastricht criteria for joining
the Euro and will meet the deadline.
</P>
<P>
But the dissolution of parliament is widely regarded as a bold
action by Chirac to push forward the European construction, which is
becoming more and more controversial not only in France, but also in
Germany and other European countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970422.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Authorities' Diplomacy With Money Criticized (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
However, given the situation that the world community commonly
acknowledges "one China," the Taiwan authorities' acts can gain no
favor internationally.
</P>
<P>
According to an old Chinese saying, "Anything obtained through
improper interests is sure to lose due to the interests." The
"establishment of diplomatic relations" bought by the Taiwan
authorities can easily end at any time, because some requests
cannot be met.
</P>
<P>
The desire for money has prompted some countries to "sever
diplomatic relations" and "resume diplomatic relations" over and
over with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Since 1996 when South Africa declared it would "sever
diplomatic relations" with Taiwan by the end of this year, some
countries that had been highly paid by the Taiwan authorities to
guarantee "diplomatic relations" have also begun to put a stop to
the practice. And Taiwan's "pragmatic diplomacy" has been in
question.
</P>
<P>
The article says it is commonly recognized that there is only
one China in the world, that the People's Republic of China is the
sole legal representative of China, and that Taiwan is part of
China.
</P>
<P>
Under such circumstances, any action of the Taiwan authorities
to gain international status with money cannot succeed, the
article points out.
</P>
<P>
According to some insightful people on the island, the Taiwan
authorities should have a clear view of the current international
situation and the general strength of the motherland's mainland,
and realize that "the diplomatic breakthrough and the safety
guarantee of Taiwan rely on the relaxation of the cross-straits
relations."
</P>
<P>
Only after the reunification is achieved between the two sides
of the Taiwan Straits can the compatriots on both sides share the
dignity and reputation enjoyed by the Chinese people in the world,
the article says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
