<HEADLINE> Greece Not Satisfied With Italian Cooperation: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Greece today voiced its
dissatisfaction with Greek-Italian cooperation in the framework of
the multinational security force policing the distribution of
humanitarian aid in the strife-ridden Albania.
</P>
<P>
Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas said today that the
cooperation between the two countries was developing under
"difficult conditions."
</P>
<P>
"We want a more substantial cooperation in order to overcome
problems and speed up our pace so that we will be able to respond
to our role," he said, referring to the Greek force's slow march
towards its port of destination, Vlore, in southern Albania.
</P>
<P>
The second company of 520 Greek troops left for Albania today
while the first part of the Greek force remains at Fieri, awaiting
the green light from the Italian command to move to Vlore.
</P>
<P>
Greek Defense Undersecretary Dimitris Apostolakis today also
stressed that the Greek mission would remain "neutral and
impartial" and would not interfere in Albania's domestic affairs.
</P>
<P>
A total of 760 Greek troops are expected to participate in the
U.N.-mandated operations in Albania which will last three months.
</P>
<P>
Most of the Greek troops will be stationed in the Albanian
capital of Tirana while another company will be deployed in Vlore.
</P>
