<HEADLINE> Iran Allows Private Banks at Free Trade Zones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Iranian banking authorities
announced here today that the private sector is allowed to
set up banks at the free trade and industrial zones with
partnership of the public sector.
</P>
<P>
Mohsen Nourbakhsh, Governor of the Central Bank of Iran
(CBI), said that the central government has decided to authorize
establishment of the banks at the free trade zones.
</P>
<P>
The governor made the statement at the opening ceremony of
a branch of the Export Promotion Bank of Iran at Qeshm Free
Trade and Industrial Zone, about 1,000 kilometers south of Tehran.
</P>
<P>
He said that the decision was made in line with a plan
passed by the Expediency Council which is headed by President
Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani.
</P>
<P>
"Foreign banks are also allowed to open branches at the free
trade zones and the domestic banks are entitled to perform
external operations there," he was quoted by the official news
agency IRNA as saying.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his hope that the free trade zones would
earn more value-added profits.
</P>
<P>
Iran has made little progress in absorbing foreign investment
though it pledged guarantee for the safety of foreign investment
in his country in a bid to lure capitals from other countries.
</P>
<P>
Iran has set forth a series of regulations and rules regarding
to investment, customs, import and export business, monetary and
banking operations and utilization of land and natural resources
in favor of foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
However, foreign investors still feel great political and
business risks in the country as they believe the regulations are
still not perfect enough for them. It has to take a long way to
reach the goal to make the zones centers of attracting advanced
technologies and of trade.
</P>
<P>
There are three free trade zones, namely Kish Island, Qeshm
Island and Chabahar. They are all situated at the south
coast of the country and connected to major international
waterways via the Persian Gulf and the Oman Sea and finally
the Indian Ocean. 
</P>
</TEXT>
