<HEADLINE> S. Africa Pledges Support to Mid-East Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 21 (Xinhua) -- South Africa would like to
play a constructive role in the Middle East peace process, but
would not become directly involved in the process, Deputy Foreign
Affairs Minister Aziz Pahad said today.
</P>
<P>
Opening a workshop in Pretoria, Pahad said the South African
government hopes peace efforts in the Middle East will be revived
soon to replace centuries of conflict.
</P>
<P>
This should be done by offering encouragement for successes
and expressing disappointment at failures through what he called
carefully-crafted statements, said Pahad.
</P>
<P>
He also said South Africa's policy towards the countries in
the region will be underpinned by the principle of
evenhandedness, adding good relations with one country do not
preclude good relations with the other.
</P>
<P>
The workshop, organized by the Department of Foreign Affairs,
was aimed at explaining and refining foreign policy approaches to
the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
It examined ways to improve South Africa's understanding of
the endemic factors threatening peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
A wide range of academics, politicians, business leaders,
non-government bodies and media representatives attended the
workshop. 
</P>
