<HEADLINE> African Social Security Seminar Opens in Harare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 21 (Xinhua) -- A five-day seminar on social
security started here today, gathering experts from 22 English
speaking African countries.
</P>
<P>
The experts are expected to formulate and implement
appropriate strategies for social protection reform.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean Public Service, Labor and Social Welfare Minister
Florence Chitauro told the experts that limited resources in
Zimbabwe have hindered the National Social Security Authority
(NSSA) from including civil servants and domestic workers among
its contributors.
</P>
<P>
The NSSA was set up by the government as a compulsory pension
scheme in October 1994 and now draws about 6.36 million U.S.
Dollars from its members countrywide.
</P>
<P>
The scheme is designed to benefit members by giving them funds
during periods of income stoppage or reduction, such as when
invalid, at retirement and to survivors of a member at and after
his or her death.
</P>
<P>
When it became operational, civil servants, domestic workers
and self-employed people were "temporarily" exempted from
contributing to the scheme, which has included all workers in the
private sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
