<HEADLINE> Russian Official on Relations with China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Russia and China enjoy mutual
confidence and have set an example of sound tendencies in
international relations, Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Grigory
Karasin said today.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of a state visit by Chinese President Jiang Zemin to
Moscow, Karasin told the Itar-Tass news agency that the sound
"tendencies are not the widening of blocs but, quite the contrary,
the stepping up of confidence measures."
</P>
<P>
During Jiang's visit, Karasin said, the heads of five states --
Russia, China, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan -- will sign
an agreement on mutual reduction of military forces in boder areas.
</P>
<P>
Calling the agreement a "very important document", Karasin said
"this is an significant measure of confidence between the five
countries. The tendency of cooperation and confidence becomes a
consistent line, which is extremely important for the Asia-Pacific
region and the whole world."
</P>
<P>
Karasin also said the document will be fully in keeping with
Russia's interests. The Russian Defense Ministry directly
participated in drafting the document, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Russian official said the sound tendencies have a positive
effect on other countries, citing the agreement between China and
India on confidence-building measures in the military field in
border areas signed in November 1996, about seven months after the
Shanghai accord signed by China, Russia, Kazakhstan Kyrgyzstan and
Tajikistan on confidence-building in the military field in border
areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
