<HEADLINE> Cargo Handled by Tanzania Harbours to Be Declined </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzania Harbours Authority
(THA) is expected to handle 5.07 million tons of cargo this financial
year compared to 5.8 million tons handled last financial year.
</P>
<P>
The THA Director General, Sammson Luhigo told the authority's
Workers Council meeting held here today that the slight cargo
consignment drop experienced was due to change of import sourcing
point.
</P>
<P>
"Most of our potential customers such as Zambia and some Central
African countries are now importing from South Africa instead of the
European countries as it was the case before," explained Luhigo.
</P>
<P>
The THA chief also attributed the decline of cargo at the port to
poor performance of economy in countries which have been major
customers for years.
</P>
<P>
Luhigo said that the authority was taking proper measures to ensure
that the amount of cargo to be handled was increased and maintained at
a substantial level.
</P>
<P>
"We are dedicated to improve our operational capacity in cargo
handling," emphasized the director general, adding that the authority
was about to start expanding the port's mouth.
</P>
<P>
He said that better services would enable the authority to compete
effectively under the trade liberalization and privatisation process.
</P>
<P>
The director general also said Mtwara and Tanga ports are operating
below capacity.
</P>
<P>
For example, he said, Tanga port has dropped from 250,000 tons down
to 100,000 tons a year, he said.  enditem

