<HEADLINE> Final Session of Leadership for Environment, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 21 (Xinhua) -- A 13-day final session of the
Leadership for Environment and Development (LEAD) started here
today.
</P>
<P>
Over 100 participants from China, India, Canada, Indonesia,
Nigeria, Mexico, Pakistan, Brazil and southern Africa are
attending the session.
</P>
<P>
They will discuss relations between environment and
development and make an on-the-spot investigation on development
in Nyanga district of east Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Opening the session, Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe said
the primary aim of environmental management should be to ensure
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said excessive demands are already being made on the
environment's limited resources and on the carrying capacity of
the fragile resources, adding that any economic prosperity that
disregards environmental concerns could not be sustainable.
</P>
<P>
Leadership for Environment and Development, or the LEAD
program, is a non-profit organization that seeks to bring
together a generation of international leaders to carry forth a
vision of sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
The LEAD program was established in direct response to the
growing need for collaborative action in support of the world's
natural and human resources.
</P>
<P>
Following extensive research by prominent individuals in the
field, the Rockefeller Foundation officially launched the LEAD
program in 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
