<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The Industrial Bank of Kuwait (IBK) has
extended 15.6 million Kuwaiti dinars (51.48 U.S. dollars) to
finance 15 projects in 1996 in an effort to diversify the economy
in Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The bank said in its report published here today that the
total costs of the projects reached around 35.5 million dinars
(117.15 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The IBK is a state-run financial institute mainly in charge of
operations relating to industrial sector in the country.
</P>
<P>
The bank was founded late in 1973 with a capital of 10 million
dinars (33 million U.S. dollars) grouping a number of
shareholders including the Ministry of Finance, Central Bank of
Kuwait, the Public Institution for Social Security, Kuwait Real
Estate Bank, five commercial banks in addition to a number of
investment companies.
</P>
<P>
-- Kuwait and Indonesia will open a new air route to expand
commercial cooperation between the two countries and meet the
increasing demands of exchanges in various fields.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Airways Corporation, the only state-run airways
company in the country, was currently discussing plans to open a
new route to the Indonesian island of Bali, the second destination
of the company in Indonesia after Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
An agreement was expected to be signed after next meeting
scheduled to be held later this year. Final preparations for the
opening of the Bali route were also postponed until next meeting.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait Airways Corporation now flies more than 30 destinations
around the world.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The U.S. will give Jordan 200 million U.S. dollars in
renewable short-term and medium-term financial aid under an
agreement to take effect today.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian newspaper Al-Dustour today quoted local sources
as saying that the agreement, signed by the Jordanian government
and the U.S. Export and Import Bank, aims to provide Jordan the
money necessary for the imports of U.S. products.
</P>
<P>
The agreement will enable Jordanian banks to open U.S.-dollar
accounts for their customers to finance their imports from the
U.S. on guarantees from the Central Bank of Jordan, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Jordanian banks should open documentary
credits for imports from the U.S. through either the Arab Bank
in New York or the City Bank in the largest U.S. city.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Arab Development Fund has helped provided 107,900
job opportunities in Egypt through collaboration with the Social
Fund for Development (SFD) this year.
</P>
<P>
A SFD report said that the Arab fund financed 21 projects in
the Egyptian governorates with a total value of 155.5 million
Egyptian pounds (45 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the Abu Dhabi Fund financed six projects with a total
value of 168.9 million Egyptian pounds (more than 49 million
dollars) and the Kuwaiti Fund has financed 17 projects with a
total value of 155.6 million Egyptian pounds (45.7 million
dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
