<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac Dissolves Parliament, Announces Early Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 21 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
made his much expected radio-television speech this evening on the
dissolution of the French parliament and the organization of early
legislative elections on May 25 and June 1.
</P>
<P>
After weeks of silence over rumors about the dissolution until
today, Chirac appeared on television with a smile and began his
speech with the straight forward announcement of the parliamentary
dissolution.
</P>
<P>
"My dear compatriots, after consultation with the prime
minister, president of the senate and president of the National
Assembly, I have decided to dissolve the National Assembly," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Although Chirac has given the French people enough time to
prepare for his decision by letting the rumors spread for weeks
without seriously denying them, his decision still came as an
action of gamble.
</P>
<P>
The dissolution is widely believed to be aimed at avoiding an
overlap of the timing of the legislative elections, originally
scheduled for the spring of 1998, and the nearing of the deadline
for meeting the Maastricht Treaty criteria for joining the
European single currency, the euro.
</P>
<P>
"My dear compatriots, the time has come for you to speak for
yourselves," said Chirac, adding that he wanted to "give the
speech back to the people, in order that they can express
themselves clearly on the fullness and the rhythm of changes to
come in the next five years."
</P>
<P>
"Today, I think, with conscience, that the interest of the
country commands the moving forward of the elections," he said.
</P>
<P>
He called on the French people to support the country's efforts
to join the European Monetary Union (EMU), and in the construction
of a strong European Union because, he said, "union makes power."
</P>
<P>
"For meeting the deadline (of joining EMU) in a position of
force, for constructing a Europe which is respectful of the genius
of the (European) nations which make it up, and which is capable
of rivaling great powers of the world, your adhesion and your
support are essential," said Chirac.
</P>
<P>
He also called on the French voters to "give France a majority
which will have the force and the necessary time for defying the
challenges of today."
</P>
<P>
"Nothing is easy, but we should choose the good road, the one
which puts together justice, solidarity and modernity," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
