<HEADLINE> Landmines Meeting Turning Point for Southern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 21 (Xinhua) -- A meeting of member states
of the Southern African Development Community (SADC) will mark a
turning point in efforts to free the region of landmines, the
International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) said today.
</P>
<P>
The remarks were made by ICRC President Cornelio Sommaruga in
Pretoria in a response to the opening of the three-day meeting in
Harare, capital of Zimbabwe, earlier today.
</P>
<P>
Sommaruga said there are more than 30 million landmines on
African continent, causing both human suffering and bringing
social and economic burdens to the governments.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, organized by the ICRC and the Organization of
African Unity, will discuss regional and international
cooperation in mine clearance on the continent.
</P>
<P>
It also offered an opportunity for the states of southern
Africa to take a leading role in the international efforts to
eliminate one of the great scourges of the 20th century, said a
statement by the ICRC Office in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was specifically requested at the October 1996
seminar on landmines in Ottawa, Canada, at which 50 states voted
in favor of a total ban on landmines, said the statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
