<HEADLINE> Democrats Warn Republicans on Chemical Weapons Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Democratic Party
today warned that Republicans will bear the responsibility if the
Senate does not approve the Chemical Weapons Convention this week.
</P>
<P>
The 100-member Senate is expected to start its debate on the
convention Wednesday and vote Thursday. The treaty needs 67 votes,
a two-thirds majority, for approval.
</P>
<P>
"Whether or not we pass the chemical weapons treaty comes down
to whether or not there are 22 Republicans who are willing to
provide the necessary votes," Senate Democratic Leader Tom Daschle
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"This is as critical an issue as we will find this Congress, or
perhaps this decade," he said. "It is a remarkable important
document that requires U.S. participation and support."
</P>
<P>
The treaty, which bans development, production, stockpiling,
transferring and use of chemical weapons, has been signed by more
than 160 countries and ratified by more than 70 of them. It will
go into effect on April 29.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. will not participate in the treaty if the Senate fails
to approve it.
</P>
<P>
"The Republican Caucus is going to have to decide whether it
wants to be part of the international community or whether it
wants to avoid making the responsibilities and taking on the
initiatives necessary to ensure that we can continue to play the
role of superpower for the world," Daschle said.
</P>
<P>
"It is a battle for the heart and soul of the Republican
Party," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
