<HEADLINE> S. Leone's Rebel Leader not Under House Arrest in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, April 21 (Xinhua) - Sierra Leone's Information
Minister Abdul Bangura said today that disputed rebel leader
Foday Sankoh "is not under house arrest" in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua, Bangura said, "he is a guest of
the Nigerian government".
</P>
<P>
Western diplomats here said they were "startled" by the
remarks as it added a further confusion on the status of Sankoh
in Nigeria where he has been for the past four weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian Embassy in Sierra Leone issued a statement
recently, saying Sankoh was being investigated on arms carrying
charges.
</P>
<P>
Since then, there has not been any further announcement and
Sankoh in interviews with the BBC had insisted he was not being
held against his will.
</P>
<P>
About three weeks ago, a group of Sankoh's loyalists kidnapped
up to eight officials including Sierra Leone Ambassador to
Guinea Mohamed Diaby, when they went to the rebel camp in far
eastern Sierra Leone to negotiate a replacement of Sankoh.
</P>
<P>
Government officials said the group holding the hostages over
the weekend warned the Sierra Leone government that unless Sankoh
is released from Nigeria, they will attack the capital Freetown.
</P>
<P>
Information Minister Bangura said that he is sceptical about
the threat. "How can they say so when dozens of their colleagues
are surrendering to tribal chiefs in the north?", he asked.
</P>
</TEXT>
