<HEADLINE> French Cease-Fire Monitor Demands Israeli Pullout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 21 (Xinhua) -- A French chief delegate in a
committee supervising breaches of cease-fire on the
Lebanese-Israeli border said here today that the five-nation
committee "can't prevent the tension in south Lebanon with an
Israeli presence there."
</P>
<P>
Jean-Michel Gaussot, head of the French delegation in the
cease-fire monitoring committee, said that only an implementation
of U.S. Security Council Resolution 425, rather than the
committee, is a solution for the south Lebanon problem.
</P>
<P>
Gaussot visited today the Beirut Presidential Palace and
briefed to Lebanese President Elias Hrawi on "works of the
monitoring group, especially during the French chairmanhood, which
started on November 1 and will end on April 30."
</P>
<P>
After a cease-fire understanding between Lebanon and Israel on
April 26, 1996, the committee was established comprising the United
states, France, Israel, Lebanon and Syria. The five-member
committee should be presided in rotation among its members.
</P>
<P>
"Of course this group is not a solution for the south Lebanon
problem, which will only be solved through an implementation of
Resolution 425 or a peace agreement between Lebanon and Syria on
the one side and Israel on the other," Gaussot said.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Security Council Resolution 425 calls for an unconditional
Israeli withdrawal from one tenth of Lebanon's territory the
Jewish state occupied in 1978.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters at the end of his meeting with the
Lebanese president, Gaussot expressed his hope that the tension in
south Lebanon, which is unavoidable as long as Israel refuses to
pull its forces out of the region, would not negatively affect the
civilians.
</P>
<P>
He said, "I think as long as this (Israeli) presence remains,
there is a certain tension, but this tension should not negatively
affect the civilians."
</P>
<P>
The French diplomat also expressed hope that members in the
cease-fire monitoring team will continue to play a "correct role"
after the U.S. taking the chairmanhood from the next
month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
