<HEADLINE> Canada's Inflation Up Slightly in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Canadian consumers paid an average
of 0.2 percent more in March for the goods and services contained
in the Consumer Price Index basket, Statistics Canada said today.
</P>
<P>
The federal agency attributed the slight increase, relative to
February, to price hikes in clothing and footwear, air travel,
packaged travel tours, piped gas and cable television services.
</P>
<P>
However, it said, the rises were partly offset by declines in
gasoline and fuel oil prices, and in mortgage interest charges.
</P>
<P>
The inflation in March was equivalent to a 2.0 percent annual
rate, slightly lower than the previous three months' 2.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Between March 1996 and March 1997, annual increases in
provincial inflation rate ranged from a low of 0.9 percent in
British Columbia to a high of 3.5 percent in Newfoundland.
</P>
<P>
The extreme low inflation in British Columbia was due largely
to sharp drops in the owned accommodation and auto insurance
indexes, Statistics Canada said.
</P>
<P>
Newfoundland's high rate was the result of larger-than-expected
increases in six of its major component indexes, including food,
clothing and footwear. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
