<HEADLINE> Clinton Heads for Flooded Upper Midwest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Departing for the flooded
upper Midwest, U.S. President Bill Clinton today promised a "very
creative" approach to help Dakotans rebuild homes.
</P>
<P>
Clinton was flying to Grand Forks, North Dakota, for a
helicopter tour of the flood-plagued town, where the Red River
swelled over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
He said he was confident that the Congress would approve an
extraordinary aid plan for the flooded region.
</P>
<P>
Clinton was to tour the Grand Forks area by helicopter and then
meet rescue workers and refugees at the Grand Forks Air Force
Base, some 26 kilometers west of the river. More than 2,000
evacuees are staying there.
</P>
<P>
Sewage-fouled river water covered 75 percent of Grand Forks and
virtually all of neighboring East Grand Forks, Minnesota, on
Monday. A large section of downtown Grand Forks was destroyed by
fire.
</P>
<P>
Erskine Bowles, White House chief of staff, discussed recovery
plans for the upper Midwest with Cabinet members on Monday and
later met the North Dakota and South Dakota congressional
delegations.
</P>
<P>
All of the Dakotas and much of Minnesota have been declared
federal disaster areas.
</P>
<P>
A team of federal officials was flying into Bismarck, North
Dakota. 
</P>
