<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-US Cooperation In Management Training </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- China and the United States will
cooperate in training high-ranking managerial personnel from
China's large-sized state-owned enterprises, it was announced
today.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Academy of Sciences and the State Economic and
Trade Commission this afternoon signed an agreement with the
America-based Computer Associates International (CA), the
second-largest software company in the US, in the People's Great
Hall.
</P>
<P>
The project is meant to upgrade the management skills in
China's large state firms, and to promote the development of the
country's information industry.
</P>
<P>
Under the project, some 100 top Chinese personnel will attend
classes in prestigious universities in the US, work in CA's
headquarters and worldwide branches, and visit large-scale US
enterprises over a three-year period.
</P>
<P>
The three sides are to set up a management committee, and to
select qualified trainees for the project, sources said, adding
that the first group will go to the US later this year.
</P>
<P>
The CA is one of the world's largest software
manufacturers. Its president, Charles B. Wang, is an
American-Chinese who was born in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Also attending today's ceremony were Lu Jiaxi, vice-chairman of
the National People's Congress Standing Committee, and Zhu
Guangya, vice-chairman of the National Committee of the Chinese
People's Political Consultative Conference.  
</P>
</TEXT>
