<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK House Prices Rise 5 Pct in 1st Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 22 (Xinhua) -- House prices in some parts of
Britain have risen by more than 5 percent in the first three
months of this year, according to a survey published today.
</P>
<P>
More than 10 percent of the 259 estate agents surveyed by the
Royal Institute of Chartered Surveyors (RICS) said that house
prices had risen at least 5 percent in the past quarter, the
biggest rise recorded since prices boomed in 1988.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the institution said that the housing market
seemed to be immune to the impending general election, and even
the predicted interest rate rise in early May was unlikely to have
any appreciable effect.
</P>
<P>
However, the RICS denied that the UK was in the grip of a new
housing boom, saying that there were great regional differences in
price performance and demand was not as great as in the late 1980s
and sales were lower.
</P>
<P>
It added that most of the recent upsurge in prices were due to
the buoyancy of markets in a few regions, such as London,
southeast England and the west Midlands, while in other parts of
the country, the recovery had been much more subdued.
</P>
<P>
Transactions, the measure of demand, are currently being made
at a rate of 1.3 million per year compared with the 2.2 million
achieved in 1988. 
</P>
</TEXT>
