<DOCNO> XIE19970422.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liu Guoliang Finally Wins Waldner's Respect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANCHESTER, England, April 22 (Xinhua) -- To win the respect of
the world proudest table tennis player isn't easy.
</P>
<P>
After three consecutive losses with the first one dating back
to 1992, Sweden's Jan-Ove Waldner finally admits Chinese Liu
Guoliang is the best.
</P>
<P>
"I predict the world men's singles title will go to very
talented Liu," said 31-year-old Waldner on Tuesday, the only
player in the world to have won a Grand Slam of the Olympic, world
championship and World Cup titles.
</P>
<P>
It took Liu four years to get the credit from Waldner. The
20-year-old Chinese, who bagged two gold medals in the Atlanta
Olympics last summer and snatched the World Cup two months later,
is now one trophy away from the Swede's greatness.
</P>
<P>
"I have confidence," Liu told Xinhua, but he came short of
revealing how many gold medals he aimed to win in the world
championships which starts on Thursday or if he considered himself
as a favorite for the coveted single title.
</P>
<P>
Liu shot to fame as a 16-year-old at the expense of Waldner in
the China Open months before the 1992 Olympic Games, beating the
more fancied rival in straight sets.
</P>
<P>
Liu Guoliang, whose name means "pillar of the country" in
Chinese, was thus hailed as a reviver of the Chinese traditional
penhold style, which was predicted to end up in a Darwinian-style
extinction as more players were turning to handshake grip.
</P>
<P>
Playing a modified penhold style, Liu sticks rubbers onto both
sides of the racket and plays top spins with backhand.
</P>
<P>
Liu's upset victory over Waldner, who had been taking Chinese
as easy preys since two-time world champion Jiang Jialiang
retired, was a morale booster for the Chinese penholders. Most of
them have resorted to this modified style.
</P>
<P>
Waldner regarded his first loss to Liu as a mere lack of
concentration, promising to give the Chinese youngster a lesson in
their next meeting.
</P>
<P>
It was Liu who gave Waldner a lesson.
</P>
<P>
Leading by five points and with as many serves in his hands,
Waldner wilted under barrages of Liu's backhand top spins and
forehand flat shots, bowing out of the men's singles competition
at the 1995 world championships.
</P>
<P>
A complacent Waldner told reporters before this match that he
expected to take on Chinese lefthander Wang Tao in the
semi-finals. But he never made that far.
</P>
<P>
Liu's last fight with Waldner was a clash of two contrasting
styles and the world best servers. Liu took it seriously, so did
Waldner.
</P>
<P>
It turned out that Liu was a mount too high for Waldner to
scale as the Swede's rallying play was a mere interlude to Liu's
re-assertion of his authority in the game.
</P>
<P>
En route to the final against Waldner, Liu had beaten European
aces Vladimir Samsonov of Belarus, Zoran Primorac of Croatia,
Patrick Chila of France and Jean-Michael Saive of Belgium.
</P>
<P>
Recalling his 1-3 defeat in the World Cup, Waldner said his
loss could have been worse.
</P>
<P>
"I should have lost 3-0," he said. "It was a much easier game
for Liu than when I lost in the 1995 world championships where I
had led 10-5 in the final set."
</P>
<P>
Despite an impressive record against Europeans, Liu often falls
victim to his teammates and South Koreans.
</P>
<P>
He has never beaten world No. 1 Kong Linghui in major
competition and holds a poor record against Wang Tao.
</P>
<P>
South Korean Kim Taek Soo has handed two straight defeats to
Liu after the Atlanta Games.
</P>
<P>
"Asian players are familiar with my style, but European players
aren't," Liu said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
