<DOCNO> XIE19970422.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany to Join Euro Despite Missing Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Doubts about Germany's ability to
make the grade for joining the single European currency gained new
ground today as the country's six leading economic institutes
joined the pessimists' club.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the six institutes, which jointly issued a spring
economic report Tuesday, still believed that Germany would still
managed to make the first wave to join the common currency -- the
Euro, which is due to be launched on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
"Most probably, Germany would not fail to join the European
Monetary Union," they said, raising the possibility that the tough
requirements set by the European Union for Euro membership might
be softened eventually.
</P>
<P>
According to projections of the six institutes, the country's
leading think tanks, Germany would overshoot the three percent
budget deficit limit required by the EU Maastricht Treaty for
participating in the Euro.
</P>
<P>
Germany would run a budget deficit equivalent to 3.2 percent of
gross domestic product (GDP) in 1997, instead of 2.9 percent
predicted by the government, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It is also expected to miss another key Euro target by posting
a public debt of 62 percent of GDP this year, above the 60 percent
limit required by the EU Maastricht Treaty, the report added.
</P>
<P>
Under the timetable for establishing the Euro, 1997 is a
crucial year because decision on which countries will be able to
make the first wave to join the Euro is expected to be made in May
1998, based on full economic data of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Given ongoing attempts by the government to slash state
spending, the report said, it might still be possible for Germany
to meet the three percent budgetary threshold.
</P>
<P>
But it would no longer be possible for Germany to bring overall
public debt below the 60 percent mark, mainly due to the massive
costs of the 1990 German reunification, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report was written by the German Institute for Economic
Research in Berlin, the Institute for Economic Research in
Hamburg, the Institute for Economic Research in Munich, the
Institute for World Economy in Kiel, the Institute for Economic
Research in Halle and the Rheinisch-Westfaelisches Institute for
Economic Research in Essen.
</P>
<P>
The six leading economic institutes issue a state of economy
report each spring and autumn.
</P>
<P>
Their joint reports, together with the annual economic report
by the government in January and the autumn report by the so-call
"five wise men," a politically independent economic advisory
panel, are recognized as the most important economic projections
for the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
