<HEADLINE> Canada's Retail Up 1.1 Percent in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Retail sales in Canada recorded a
large increase of 1.1 percent in February, following a 1.0 percent
rise in January, Statistics Canada reported today.
</P>
<P>
With the monthly increase, said the federal government agency
in a report, Canada's total retail sales for February rose to an
equivalent of 13.4 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"While a pause was observed in December...retail sales have
been steaming ahead since October 1996. The positive results of
recent months give a strong start to 1997," it said.
</P>
<P>
Low interest rates are believed to be the driving force behind
the broadly based advances reported by Canadian retailers.
</P>
<P>
Consumers spent more in February compared with January in each
of the seven retail trade sectors in Canada.
</P>
<P>
Sales advanced the most in the general merchandise stores
sector (3.7 percent), followed by gains in the automotive sector
(1.0 percent) and furniture stores sector (2.0 percent).
</P>
<P>
Together, these three sectors accounted for over four-fifths of
the February increase, Statistics Canada said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
