<HEADLINE> Fujian Stages War Against Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Fujian Province in southeast China
will stage a campaign to prevent the spread of drugs and drug
abuse, according to a provincial working conference on drugs held
here today.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the provincial government outlined its
anti-drug duties, which include closely controlling the number of
newly-reported drug addicts, eliminating the planting of opium
poppies, destroying drug-processing plants, cracking down on drug
crimes, and strengthening the anti-drug publicity drive.
</P>
<P>
The coastal province has achieved remarkable success in its
anti-drug efforts. In 1996, it cracked 863 drug cases, three times
the figure of 1995, and it arrested a total of 836 people on drug
charges.
</P>
<P>
From 1991 to 1996, the province had solved 1,453 cases,
destroying 38 underground workshops which make the drug "ice,"
seizing about 2,700 kg of various kinds of drugs, and capturing
more than 2,000 criminals.
</P>
<P>
Efforts have also been made to help drug addicts kick the
habit, with drug rehabilitation centers being built in Fuzhou,
Xiamen, and Fuqing.
</P>
<P>
More than 3,000 substance abusers in the province reportedly
have quit using drugs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
