<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Determination to Enter WTO Consistent: Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng said here
today that China's policy on entering the World Trade Organization
is consistent, and the issue of China's entry shouldn't be
politicalized.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with WTO director-general Renato Ruggiero, Li
reiterated that the requirements for China's entry should not
exceed its present economic development level.
</P>
<P>
Li thanked Ruggiero for his concern over China's accession to
the organization, saying China attaches great importance to the
multi-lateral trade mechanism represented by WTO, and supports its
role in world economy and trade.
</P>
<P>
At present, economic links between countries as well as
regional coordination are improving, and this is beneficial to
both bilateral and multi-lateral economic and trade cooperation,
the Premier said.
</P>
<P>
Any country and region that wants to seek economic development
should reinforce economic and trade coordination, Li said, adding
that China has strengthened its economic ties with the outside
world through reform and opening up.
</P>
<P>
The Premier said that China's development cannot be separated
from the world, and in return, the world development is
inseparable from China. China will continue its talks with
relevant countries proceeding from the balance between rights and
obligations, he said.
</P>
<P>
Since the latter half of last year, negotiations on China's
entry have witnessed certain progress. However, Li said, China is
still a developing country with imbalanced development.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the world economic and trade situation is
still characterized by inequality, exchange of unequal value, and
power politics such as imposing sanctions. This conforms neither
to the principle of equality and mutual benefit, nor to the
developing trend of the world situation and relations, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Ruggiero said that over the past few days, he visited both
China's developing cities and relatively backward countryside, and
China's reform, opening up and economic progress left a deep
impression on him.
</P>
<P>
China's entry to the WTO benefits not only China but the world
as a whole, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The Director-General, who has always been concerned about
China's entry to the WTO, said he will continue his efforts for
the promotion of negotiations in a bid to realize China's early
entry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970422.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Largest Desert Oilfield Goes into Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The Tazhong No.4 Oilfield,
China's largest desert oilfield lying in the Tarim Basin of the
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, recently went into operation,
with daily crude output topping 5,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
According to a China National Petroleum Corp (CNPC) source, the
oilfield was discovered by the Tarim Oil Exploration Headquarters
in the heartland of the Taklimakan Desert in 1992, which covers a
total oil-bearing area of 35.7 sq km and has oil reserves of over
93 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The CNPC source noted that the oilfield was first explored on a
trial basis in 1994, with an expected annual crude production
capacity of two million tons. A total of 40 oil wells have been
sunk over the past three years, using advanced desert drilling
technology.
</P>
<P>
To date, the Tazhong No.4 Oilfield has developed an updated oil
storage installation and a computer monitoring system. The crude
turned out by the oilfield is piped to the city of Korla, some 500
km away.
</P>
<P>
The Tazhong No.4 Oilfield is the fifth that has been developed
in the Tarim Basin, which together with the other four has
produced an annual crude output of 4.4 million tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
