<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Table Tennis Worlds, A Show for Oldies? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANCHESTER, England, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Andrzej Grubba,
Jan-Ove Waldner and Johnny Huang have proved that table tennis
isn't a sport only for the young.
</P>
<P>
Even though table tennis requires reflexes, agility, power and
speed, those no longer as quick about court as before insist they
can catch up with the young through their experiences.
</P>
<P>
"Table tennis is an art more than a sport and its minute and
fine maneuvers can be easily done by those players with
experiences," said Grubba, the oldest player among the world top
20 who is to celebrate his 39th birthday nine days after the world
championships ends on May 5.
</P>
<P>
The Polish star, nicknamed a "table tennis comedian" for his
on-court gimmicks, amazed Chinese officials after winning the
Malaysian Open last year which had a strong field including
China's world top players Kong Linghui and Liu Guoliang, both at
20.
</P>
<P>
"It's incredible," said Li Furong, former world champion and
now a top sports official in China. "Chinese should learn from
Europeans on how to prolong the career."
</P>
<P>
Waldner, who won Sweden's only gold medal in the Barcelona
Olympic Games, never showed his years in the Qatar Open in
February, the last major tournament before the world championships.
</P>
<P>
The 31-year-old Waldner nipped world champion Kong Linghui for
the fourth straight time in the semi-finals and beat the
20-year-old European top player Vladimir Samsonov from Belarus for
the 30,000 U.S. dollars winner's prize. He also combined with his
30-year-old teammate Jorgen Persson to take the team top honor.
</P>
<P>
Waldner is to lead an aging Swedish men's team, whose youngest
member is 28-year-old Peter Karlsson, for a crack at the world
team championship which they had been holding for six years before
being dethroned by China in the 1995 Worlds.
</P>
<P>
Chinese sports officials have put their players on high alert
against the Swedish team.
</P>
<P>
Xu Yinsheng, president of the the Chinese Table Tennis
Association who also heads International Table Tennis Federation,
warned last month that rising complacency might cost the Chinese
gold medals in the Manchester championships.
</P>
<P>
"Some players think the aging Swedish team is now easy to deal
with, it's completely wrong," said Xu, also vice minister of the
Chinese Physical Culture and Sports Commission.
</P>
<P>
"Age means experience. Don't belittle Waldner, Persson and
(Erik) Lindh," Xu warned.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Johnny Huang and Frenchman Jean-Philippe Gatien are
other old-timers tipped to shine in Manchester.
</P>
<P>
Huang, 34, regained his form in the Atlanta Games, foiling
Waldner's hope to defend the singles title, while 1993 world
champion Gatien, 29, has found his touch after lifting the elite
title in the European top 12 tournament in February.
</P>
<P>
There are many old players active in the women's table tennis
as well. Japanese Koyama Chire, 32, Cha Po Wa of Hong Kong, 31,
Geng Lijuan of Canada, 34, Chen Jing of Chinese Taipei, 28, are
expected to challenge the Chinese team led by world No. 1 Deng
Yaping. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970422.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ansett Australia To Initiate Sydney-Shanghai Route </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Ansett Australia, one of the two
air carriers in Australia, is to initiate in early June a
twice-a-week flight between Sydney and Shanghai, the company's
first route to China, General Manager of Ansett International
Craig Wallace said here today.
</P>
<P>
The new service will allow Ansett to contribute to the
developing trade and tourism growth between Australia and China,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ongoing PATA (Pacific Asia Travel Association)
46th annual conference today, Wallace said, "Operating to Shanghai
gives us access to one of the region's fastest-growing inbound
markets."
</P>
<P>
"That growth provides our airline with considerable opportunity
to increase our strength in the highly-competitive Asian market,"
he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
He added Ansett would also provide air service to the emerging
outbound tourism market, which is expected to deliver a total of
350,000 Chinese visitors per year to Australia by 2001.
</P>
<P>
The number of passengers traveling between Australia and China
has increased by close to 30 percent over the past three years,
according to the Australian Tourist Commission.
</P>
<P>
Wallace noted that Ansett has reached a commercial agreement
with the Shanghai-based China Eastern Airlines, which provides for
ground handling operations, potential code-shared flights between
the two countries, and domestic flights to cities within China
Eastern's extensive internal network.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that Ansett plans to increase the number of flights
between Sydney and Shanghai to four times a week by this November,
and to six times by November 1998, adding that it hopes to open
flights to other Chinese cities such as Beijing in the future.
</P>
<P>
Ansett, which has focused on the domestic market for decades,
started its first international service to Denpasar, Indonesia, in
1993. It now operates international flights to eight destinations,
all in the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
The carrier opened its first China office in Shanghai last
month, according to Wallace.
</P>
<P>
Air China and Quantas, the two countries' flag carriers, are
now each operating twice-a-week flights between Beijing and
Sydney, and China Eastern initiated a Beijing-Shanghai-Sydney
service last September, also twice a week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
