<HEADLINE> Chocolate-flavored Carrots On Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Chocolate-flavored carrots and
pizza-flavored corn went on sale on Monday, as the Cancer Research
Campaign (CRC) joined forces with the frozen food chain, Iceland,
to encourage children to eat vegetables.
</P>
<P>
Baked-bean-flavored peas and cheese and onion-flavored
cauliflower are also among a new range of frozen vegetables aimed
at children, the Daily Telegraph reported here today.
</P>
<P>
Professor Gordon McVie, director general of the CRC, who
suggested the idea, said about 300,000 people a year got cancer
and one-third of the cases were thought to be related to poor diet.
</P>
<P>
"There is a clear link between a diet high in vegetables and
cancer prevention, yet recent research highlighted that mums are
losing the battle to get their kids to eat vegetables," said McVie.
</P>
<P>
He said he came up with the idea when shopping in a
supermarket. He saw a huge variety of flavored crisps (potato
chips) and it occurred to him that the same could be done with
vegetables.
</P>
<P>
"These products are designed for children. Adults in the main
are not thrilled with them," said Malcolm Walker, chairman of
Iceland. "We expect to sell these products in great quantities."
</P>
<P>
Frozen food stores will sell chocolate-flavored carrots for 99
pence for a one pound bag or 1.29 pounds for a two-pound
bag. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
