<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Waldner, Samsonov Top Chinese "Blacklist" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANCHESTER, England, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Sweden's 1992 Olympic
champion Jan-Ove Waldner and Belarus' rising star Vladimir
Samsonov have been "blacklisted" as the top threats to the Chinese
table tennis players bidding for a repeat of the seven-title sweep
at the World Table Tennis Championships.
</P>
<P>
Old enemies are still there and young foes are coming, Chinese
sports officials warn their players who have allegedly become
complacent after sweeping the table tennis titles in the Atlanta
Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
Waldner, 31, the only table tennis Grand Slam winner in the
world and one of the sport's all time greats, is just one of the
old enemies whereas 20-year-old Samsonov has become a foe worthy
of Chinese steel.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese team, which wrapped up all seven events in the 1995
Worlds in the northern Chinese city of Tianjin, faces an uphill
battle to regain as much glory here because of an enlarging army
of rivals.
</P>
<P>
A "blacklist" of title contenders from outside China, drawn by
Chinese coaches Cai Zhenhua and Lu Yuansheng, rates Waldner and
Samsonov as China's No. 1 threats among the eight "very strong
rivals".
</P>
<P>
Waldner, the only player in the world who has won the Olympic,
world championship and World Cup titles, showed his killing
instinct in the Qatar Open in February, taking the men's singles
event after leading an aging Swedish squad atop the team podium.
</P>
<P>
The Swede, who suffered an early exit partly because of thumb
injury at the Atlanta Olympic Games last summer, is able to peak
at the right time, said Cai Zhenhua, Waldner's major rival in the
1980s who now heads the Chinese men's team.
</P>
<P>
"Waldner is a man of magic," Cai said. "He may play poorly in a
lesser tournament, but when a big event like world championships
comes, he can easily motivate himself."
</P>
<P>
Waldner, known for his deceptive serves and supreme ability to
change the tactics during the game, keeps a 4-0 record against
China's world No. 1 Kong Linghui and has beaten another Chinese
ace Ma Wenge twice in five months.
</P>
<P>
Samsonov, who has had the scalps of all European top players,
has given scare to Chinese after handing two recent losses to the
nation's top defensive player Ding Song, who jumped to fame after
ending the singles run of European stars Jean-Michael Saive of
Belgium and Jorgen Persson of Sweden in the last Worlds.
</P>
<P>
"Samsonov is an all-around player and he has everything a world
champion should have," Cai said.
</P>
<P>
South Korean Kim Taek Soo, German Jorg Rosskopf, Saive,
Croatian Zoran Primorac, Frenchman Jean-Philippe Gatien and Petr
Koppel from Czech Republic are other "very strong rivals" for the
Chinese men players.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese coaches also named 14 players as "serious
rivals". They include Persson, Frenchman Patrick Chila and Polish
veteran Andrzej Grubba, who is to celebrate his 39th birthday nine
days after the end of the championships.
</P>
<P>
Lu Yuansheng, head coach of the Chinese women's team, expected
his players to meet strong challenges from former Chinese playing
for their adopted countries or regions.
</P>
<P>
"The main rivals will be these players familiar with our styles
and tactics," Lu said.
</P>
<P>
Topping Lu's list of possible rivals are Chen Jing of Chinese
Taipei and Chire Koyama of Japan.
</P>
<P>
Chen Jing, the 1988 Olympic champion, won the silver medal for
Chinese Taipei both in the 1993 Worlds and the Atlanta Games.
</P>
<P>
Koyama, who caused an uproar in China with an upset victory
over China's world No. 1 Deng Yaping at the Hiroshima Asian Games
in 1994, regained her touch in the Asian championships last
December where she beat five Chinese youngsters en route to
picking up the singles title.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's Chai Po Wa, Germany's Jie Schopp and Ni Xia Lian of
Luxembourg, all former Chinese nationals, may also give some
troubles to the Chinese, Lu said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
