<DOCNO> XIE19970422.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Think Tanks Predict 2.25 Percent GDP Growth for Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Germany's leading economic
institutes predicted today that the country's gross domestic
product (GDP) will increase by 2.25 percent this year, lower than
the 2.5 percent expected by the government.
</P>
<P>
In a joint spring economic report, the six institutes, the
country's leading think tanks, said a slump in construction
industry should be blamed for the lower-than-expected GDP growth,
but exports are expected to grow by a robust 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Germany could expect a 2.75 percent GDP growth in 1998, the
country's next general election year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report also painted a gloomy picture of the job market,
predicting that unemployment will average 4.28 million people, or
11.2 percent of the workforce, in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the report commented, German Chancellor Helmut
Kohl's pledge to cut the country's jobless rate by half by the
year 2000 could be impossible to deliver.
</P>
<P>
The institutes predicted that inflation is set to remain low at
1.5 to 1.75 percent in 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
Boosted by a continued weaker dollar, the country's trade
surplus is expected to be 140 billion marks (about 82 billion
U.S. dollars) in 1998, the first time it will reach this level
since 1989, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report was written by the German Institute for Economic
Research in Berlin, the Institute for Economic Research in
Hamburg, the Institute for Economic Research in Munich, the
Institute for World Economy in Kiel, the Institute for Economic
Research in Halle and the Rheinisch-Westfaelisches Institute for
Economic Research in Essen.
</P>
<P>
The six leading economic institutes issue a state of economy
report each spring and autumn.
</P>
<P>
Their joint reports, together with the annual economic report
by the government in January and the autumn report by the so-call
"five wise men," a politically independent economic advisory
panel, are recognized as the most important economic projections
for the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
