<HEADLINE> Dhaka Can Achieve 7 Percent Growth by 2000: ESCAP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh will be able to achieve
a growth rate of up to seven percent by the year 2000 if the
current trends in the economy continue, said the Economic and
Social Cooperation of Asia and the Pacific (ESCAP) under the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Increased level of foreign direct investment and improved labor
productivity could further increase the growth rate, said an ESCAP
survey report released here today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that during the 1980s Bangladesh achieved a
growth rate of 4.3 percent, but a population growth rate of over
two percent left little room for an increase in per capita income.
</P>
<P>
However, Bangladesh has been successful in reducing average
annual inflation rate from about 10 percent in 1981-1990 to just
above four percent in 1991-1995.
</P>
<P>
The most recent trends indicate a tendency for inflation to
stabilize at that low level or to come down further, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The ESCAP further said that recent policy initiatives have
emphasized continued price stability along with greater
mobilization of domestic resources. To that end, monetary and
fiscal reforms have been carried out, the report added.
</P>
<P>
To achieve the targeted economy growth, the report also
emphasized the need for improved education, reduced corruption,
trade liberalization and regional cooperation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
