<HEADLINE> China Funds Rank Top in Performance for Third Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 22 (Xinhua) -- China equity funds came at the
top of the performance table in March with an annual return of 52
percent, a survey by the Hong Kong Investment Funds Association
(HKIFA) showed today.
</P>
<P>
This sector also came first in both January and February 1997.
</P>
<P>
Analyzing the performance of the sector, Peter Lord, vice
chairman of the HKIFA, said, "The strong returns posted were
mainly related to the strength of the China market, especially
after the interest rates reductions in May and August of 1996, and
there are further signs that inflation has slowed down."
</P>
<P>
The second leading sector was Latin American equity funds,
posting an annual return of 32 percent. In February, it also came
second on the performance table, the first time since mid-1995
when this category was added to the fund report.
</P>
<P>
Of the top 15 sectors, only four were Asian ones, namely China,
Malaysia, Hong Kong and Indonesia, while among the bottom 15
sectors, 10 were Asian-Pacific equities or warrants funds, the
survey found.
</P>
<P>
This was probably because of the concern over further
U.S. interest rates hikes after the 25 basis point increase and
the fact that several Asian countries were plagued by weak export
volumes or other domestic problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
