<DOCNO> XIE19970422.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany to Miss Euro Targets, Leading Think Tanks Predict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Doubts about Germany's ability to
make the grade for joining the single European currency gained new
ground today as the country's six leading economic institutes
joined the pessimists' club.
</P>
<P>
In a joint spring economic report released today, the six
institutes predicted that Germany would overshoot the three
percent budget deficit limit set by the European Union (EU) for
member states to qualify for the common currency -- the Euro,
which is due to be launched on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Germany would run a budget deficit equivalent to 3.2 percent of
gross domestic product (GDP) in 1997, instead of 2.9 percent
predicted by the government, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It is also expected to miss another key Euro target by posting
a public debt of 62 percent of GDP this year, above the 60 percent
limit required by the EU Maastricht Treaty, the report added.
</P>
<P>
Under the timetable for establishing the Euro, 1997 is a
crucial year because decision on which countries will be able to
make the first wave to join the Euro is expected to be made in May
1998, based on full economic data of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Given ongoing attempts by the government to slash state
spending, the report said, it might still be possible for Germany
to meet the three percent budgetary threshold.
</P>
<P>
But it would no longer be possible for Germany to bring overall
public debt below the 60 percent mark, mainly due to the massive
costs of the 1990 German reunification, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Observers said a failure of Europe's largest economy to meet
the Euro targets would raise the specter that the 1999 launch of
the Euro may have to be delayed for one or two years, or the
qualification requirements may be softened.
</P>
<P>
Germany's six leading economic institutes issue a state of
economy report each spring and autumn.
</P>
<P>
They are the German Institute for Economic Research in Berlin,
the Institute for Economic Research in Hamburg, the Institute for
Economic Research in Munich, the Institute for World Economy in
Kiel, the Institute for Economic Research in Halle and the
Rheinisch-Westfaelisches Institute for Economic Research in
Essen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970422.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore to Have Third University </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Singapore is to have its third
university to provide more opportunities for Singaporeans to
pursue studies at tertiary level, as the Singapore Institute of
Management (SIM) has decided to expand its courses with a view to
eventually attaining university status, Deputy Prime Minister Tony
Tan said today.
</P>
<P>
"The government will support SIM in its efforts to develop the
institute into a private university. Government support can
include both the provision of land and development grants as well
as per-capita recurrent grant," the deputy prime minister, who is
also in charge of the republic's current two universities, said at
an annual meeting of the SIM.
</P>
<P>
The SIM was set up in 1964 as a non-profit professional
organization to enhance managerial and organizational
effectiveness in Singapore. Over the years, the institute has
evolved and expanded to meet the needs of Singaporeans for
continuing education.
</P>
<P>
Tony Tan said, "SIM has grown from strength to strength, and
has now acquired a well-deserved reputation as a leading human
resource development organization in Singapore."
</P>
<P>
To achieve the objective of becoming a private university, the
SIM Council has decided to set up an Academic Board to be chaired
by Dr Cham Tao Soon, president of the Nanyang Technological
University.
</P>
<P>
The Academic Board will report to the SIM Council and will take
charge of academic matters and streamline courses which are
currently being conducted at SIM.
</P>
<P>
The council has also decided to appoint a task force which will
report to the Academic Board and will undertake a detailed review
of SIM's programs.
</P>
<P>
To develop SIM into a private university, Tony Tan also called
on the private sector to be "strongly involved in the running of
SIM and in determining what type of degrees or courses SIM should
conduct."
</P>
<P>
He said that the SIM should also make arrangements, possibly by
setting up a subsidiary, to continue to run the part-time programs
SIM presently offers in collaboration with foreign universities
and training institutions.
</P>
<P>
This subsidiary could also operate the Open University Degree
Program and help to cater to the needs of Singaporeans who wish to
upgrade themselves, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that it will be the task of the SIM Council to
work with the Academic Board, the Task Force and the SIM
administration to work out a strategic plan for SIM's development
into a private university complementing the present National
University of Singapore and Nanyang Technological University and
specializing in financial and business courses.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970422.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 12:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Switches to Natural Gas Option </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Maximizing natural gas utilization
has become the core of Egypt's energy strategy to protect
environment, support local demand and keep its status as a net
oil exporter, Minister of Oil Hamdi el-Banbi said here today.
</P>
<P>
Banbi told a press conference that Egypt has encouraged the
use of compressed natural gas (CNG) in vehicles since 1992, as a
substitute for polluting fuels.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the penetration of natural gas in the local market
has been real fast, either replacing liquid fuels in power
generation, partially substituting gasoline and gas oil as a
transportation fuel or partially substituting liquefied gas in
domestic sector.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, natural gas consumption reached 10.1 million tonnes,
representing about 35 percent of the total hydrocarbons
consumption compared with 12 percent in 1982, according to the
minister.
</P>
<P>
Now about 80 percent of thermal power stations have been
converted to use natural gas while natural gas has gained more
ground in the local energy scene, he said.
</P>
<P>
From 1992 up till now, 439 vehicles and 645 taxis, trucks and
buses were converted to operate with compressed natural gas
besides gas or diesel, Banbi said.
</P>
<P>
The minister pointed out that the use of 3.75 trillion cubic
feet of natural gas in different sectors from 1976-1995 has
successfully prohibited emissions of large amount of sulphur and
carbon dioxide and nitrogen oxide.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, infrastructure for the use of CNG as vehicular fuel
is steadily growing with eight refueling stations constructed and 13
others expected to operate this year.
</P>
<P>
Today, Egypt is producing an average of 900,000 barrels
of oil and 1.6 billion cubic feet of gas per day, which provides
about 92 percent of the total energy need and allows export of
surplus oil.
</P>
<P>
The so-called "natural gas option" has also contributed to
curbing the growing trend of annual oil consumption from 3
percent in 1982 to 0.3 percent in 1995, Banbi said.
</P>
<P>
The levels of oil exports was maintained at 11 million tonnes
in 1996, accounting for less than a quarter of total production,
said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Besides natural gas, Egypt also resorts to other air control
approaches, such as sulphur limitations in fuel, lead reduction
in gas and production and marketing of unleaded gas in Egypt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
