<HEADLINE> Report: Iraq Sends Helicopters to Border With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has sent helicopters to
its joint border with Saudi Arabia to carry back Iraqi pilgrims in
defying a no-fly zone enforced by U.S. warplanes, the official
Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported today.
</P>
<P>
It said that a number of helicopters flew Monday and today to
the border to bring home Iraqis returning from the annual Muslim
pilgrimage.
</P>
<P>
The helicopters flew to Arar along the Iraqi-Saudi border,
which is 350 kilometers southwest of Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
The United States urged Iraq to stay out of the no-fly zone or
face retaliation Monday following the announcement by Iraq to send
helicopters.
</P>
<P>
However, the INA Monday quoted an authoritative source as
warning the United States against molesting the Iraqi helicopters.
</P>
<P>
"Any U.S. action that threatens the security of the
helicopters and the pilgrims will be met with the suitable
response to deter aggression" because Iraq has an inalienable
right to use its civilian aircraft, the source said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq did actually exercise that right when it ran a flight
carrying a number of Iraqi pilgrims to the Saudi port city of
Jeddah on April 9, the source added.
</P>
<P>
Western allies set up the no-fly zone after the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
</TEXT>
