<DOCNO> XIE19970422.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Works for Infra-African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria is now working for having
direct access to telecommunications with other western African
countries, Lieutenant-General Oladipo Diya, the Chief of General
Staff, said in Abuja on Monday.
</P>
<P>
At a seminar on Internet services in sub-Saharan Africa, the
second-placed Nigerian leader said the project will "remove the
delay and frustration that African countries face in establishing
telecommunications link directly between themselves".
</P>
<P>
A majority of telecommunications between African countries are
currently routed through London for Anglophone countries and
Paris for Francophone countries, which makes telecommuniations
both difficult and expensive.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that African countries now pay as much as 600
million U.S. Dollars annually to the British Telecoms and French
Telecoms for calls between them.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian project, called Direct Access Multiplex, will
reduce the cost considerably, said Diya.
</P>
<P>
Stressing the importance of telecommunications infrastructure
to the development of economy and trade, he admitted that the
infrastructure in Africa is not sufficient to encourage regional
trade.
</P>
<P>
He, however, cited the coastal fibre optic project of Nigeria
and the Africa One project as examples of African nations'
efforts to improve telecommunications on the continent.
</P>
<P>
The Africa One project will link the whole coastal Africa by
fibre optic. It is now being handled by the AT&AMP;T company of the
U.S. at a cost of three billion Dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
