<HEADLINE> Japan's Lower House Calls for Okinawa Base Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Japan's House of Representatives
(lower house) adopted a resolution today calling on the government
to exert every effort toward a cut in U.S. military bases in
Okinawa.
</P>
<P>
The resolution urged the government to make utmost efforts to
consolidate, realign, reduce and relocate the U.S. bases in
Okinawa.
</P>
<P>
It also asked the government to proceed with consultations with
the United States on military postures, including the structure of
the U.S. military forces in the Asian-Pacific region, and take
comprehensive and effective measures such as "drastic reforms" to
help develop Okinawa's economy.
</P>
<P>
Majority lawmakers supported the resolution during a plenary
session, but the Japanese Communist Party, which has been calling
for a total removal of the U.S. military bases, voted against the
resolution.
</P>
<P>
Okinawa, which represents less than one percent of Japan's
total area, is home to 75 percent of all U.S. military facilities
and more than half of the 47,000 U.S. troops in Japan.
</P>
<P>
Last week, a government-proposed bill to revise legislation to
allow the continued compulsory leases of land for use by the
U.S. military was passed by the Diet (parliament). The bill has
sparked protests in Okinawa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
