<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PECC Calls For New Responses to Foster Human Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Asia Pacific economies should
introduce new forms of education and training as they now face a
major challenge of current imbalances between labor market needs
and the output of the education and training systems, the Pacific
Economic Cooperation Council (PECC) said here today.
</P>
<P>
Inadequate human resources support can put the brakes on rapid
growth in the Asia Pacific region. Thus, a fundamental policy
concern is how to keep both management's and workers' capabilities
advancing in parallel with the structural changes which underpin
the growth process, the PECC said in its latest Human Resource
Development Outlook 1996-97, which studies major labor market
issues facing the Asia Pacific economies.
</P>
<P>
The PECC Human Resource Development Outlook found that the Asia
Pacific economies are all actively pursuing policies to enhance
the output of their educational and training systems. But it said
that to cope with the changing educational and training need, "new
responses" will be required.
</P>
<P>
The proposed new responses include introducing new forms of
education and training, for example, through "twinning" between
domestic and foreign educational or training institutions, or
through distance learning arrangements, and reconsidering the
relative roles of the public and private educational and training
institutions.
</P>
<P>
The other proposals include coming up with new forms of
education and training which focus on lifelong learning and
retraining, as well as incentives for firms to upgrade their
workers' skills, and analyzing more closely the links between
foreign direct investment and the transfer of high-level skills,
and the mechanisms needed to meet the lower level manpower needs
of transnational companies.
</P>
<P>
The PECC is an independent, policy-oriented organization of
high level business, academic and government representatives from
22 Asia-Pacific economies. It aims to foster economic development
in the region by providing a forum for discussion and cooperation
in a wide range of economic areas.
</P>
<P>
The PECC Human Resource Development Outlook 1996-97 is the
fifth in an annual series published by the PECC Human Resource
Development Task Force. The PECC International Secretariat is
based in Singapore.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
