<HEADLINE> Jiang Arrives in Moscow for State Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
arrived in Moscow today for a five-day state visit to Russia
which, as Jiang says, is expected to achieve the goals of
"deepening friendship, promoting cooperation and broadening common
understanding" between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement released at the airport, Jiang said he
will hold talks with his Russian counterpart, Boris Yeltsin, to
fully exchange views on bilateral relations and major
international issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
It will be the fourth official summit between the two leaders.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Moscow, Jiang will sign a five-nation
agreement on the reduction of military forces in the border areas
with Yeltsin and the presidents of Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan and
Tajikistan, he said.
</P>
<P>
Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin and acting Foreign
Minister Igor Ivanov greeted Jiang at the airport, who is
accompanied by his wife Wang Yeping, Vice Premier and Foreign
Minister Qian Qichen and several other senior Chinese officials.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin held a ceremony at the airport to welcome Jiang's
team.
</P>
<P>
Sino-Russian relations have been soundly developed since the
beginning of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Jiang and Yeltsin announced the establishment of a
"21st century-oriented strategic partnership" between the two
countries during Yeltsin's visit to China.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said in his statement that the establishment of the
partnership is not only in line with the fundamental interests of
the two countries and two peoples, but also conducive to peace,
stability and development in the Asia-Pacific region and the world
as a whole.
</P>
<P>
A strategic partnership between the two countries is a positive
contribution to the establishment of a new international order,
Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang expressed satisfaction with the positive achievements in
cooperation in various fields between the two sides in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics showed that two-way trade rose to nearly
seven billion U.S. dollars in 1996, and is expected by the two
governments to hit 20 billion dollars by the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation between the two sides in military technology,
science, education and culture has also been on the increase in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
Chinese officials said Jiang's visit will help forge closer
ties and give fresh impetus to cooperation between the two
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
