<HEADLINE> Japanese Legislators, Ministers Visit Yasukuni Shrine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 22 (Xinhua) -- A group of 150 members of Japan's
parliament including two cabinet ministers today visited Yasukuni
Shrine in Tokyo where the Japanese war dead are enshrined.
</P>
<P>
Visits to the shrine by senior Japanese officials have always
been criticized by Japan's Asian neighbors which suffered Japanese
aggression in the years up to 1945.
</P>
<P>
Yasukuni Shrine houses the memorial tablets of Japan's war
dead, including 14 Class-A war criminals executed at the end of
World War II.
</P>
<P>
On July 29 last year, Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto visited the shrine, breaking a decade-long taboo on
prime ministerial visit to it and triggering wide-spread
condemnation.
</P>
<P>
The two cabinet members among Tuesday's visitors were Transport
Minister Makoto Koga and Director-General of Okinawa and Hokkaido
Development Agency Jitsuo Inagaki. Another 73 lawmakers sent
proxies.
</P>
<P>
The visitors belong to a group set up by the ruling Liberal
Democratic Party (LDP) in 1981 for the purpose of visiting the
Shrine.
</P>
<P>
The group was divided into two groups composed of LDP and
non-LDP members following the split of the LDP in 1993. The two
groups were reunited on April 2 this year.
</P>
<P>
The Yasukuni group comprises 228 Diet members -- 184 from the
LDP and 44 from the New Frontier Party (NFP) and other parties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
