<DOCNO> XIE19970422.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Consumer Price Indices Rise Moderately in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The Consumer Price Index (CPI)
(A), covering the largest percentage of households in Hong Kong,
recorded a 5.7 percent year-on-year growth in March, down from
that of 6.5 percent in February.
</P>
<P>
The CPI figures for March was released here today by the Census
and Statistics Department.
</P>
<P>
CPI (A) covers 50 percent households in Hong Kong whose monthly
expenditures are between 3,900 and 16,000 HK dollars (503 to 2,065
US dollars).
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, CPI (B), which is based on the expenditure
pattern of 30 percent households with expenditures between 16,000
and 28,500 HK dollars (2,064 to 3,677 US dollars), rose 5.8
percent over last year, also slower than that of 6.1 percent in
February.
</P>
<P>
However, the corresponding rate of increase in the Hang Seng
CPI, designed for 10 percent households with monthly expenditures
ranging from 28,500 to 61,000 HK dollars (2,064 to 7,870 US
dollars), was at 6.3 percent in March, slightly faster than that
of 6.2 percent in February.
</P>
<P>
The Composite CPI, covering the combined expenditure pattern of
all households, showed a year-on-year increase of 5.9 percent in
March, lower than that of 6.3 percent in February.
</P>
<P>
For the first quarter of 1997, the increase in the CPI (A)
averaged at 6.2 percent over a year earlier, while CPI (B), the
Hang Seng CPI and Composite CPI all grew by 6.1 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970422.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Maternal Mortality Rate Goes up in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The number of Uganda women dying
when giving birth has risen five times in the last 27 years,
reported the local daily New Vision today.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, 506 among every 100,000 women died due to
pregnancy-related complications, compared with 100 per 100,000
women in 1970, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Pius Okong, a consultant obstetrician and gynecologist in
Nsambya hospital, attributed the high maternal mortality rate to
a number of reasons including poor nutrition, deterioration of
health services, poverty and lack of transport in time of need.
</P>
<P>
He was quoted as advising health providers to show
responsibility towards their patients and utilize properly the
little resources available.
</P>
<P>
He also urged for basic services provided to deal with
obstertric emergencies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
