<DOCNO> XIE19970422.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Military Committee Meets in Chiefs of Staff Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 22 (Xinhua) -- NATO's Chiefs of Staff held a
one-day meeting on Tuesday at NATO headquarters with the aim of
making several recommendations to the alliance's internal and
external adaptations.
</P>
<P>
One of the meeting's major topics is the arrangement of NATO's
new command structure, especially selecting one alternative for
the commands in Europe.
</P>
<P>
According to NATO sources, the new structure is to reduce the
commands from the current 64, at four levels, to 25, at three
levels.
</P>
<P>
A senior NATO official said that the Chiefs of Staff would
probably recommend two regional commands in Europe, a Northern
Command and one for the South, instead of the current three
(North, Central and South).
</P>
<P>
They will also define the terms of responsibility of the Deputy
SACEUR (Supreme Allied Commander in Europe), who will command the
planned Combined Joint Task Forces (CJTF).
</P>
<P>
The CJTF concept, which was endorsed by foreign ministers of
NATO member states in Berlin last June, will enable NATO's
European nations to conduct their own operations using NATO assets.
</P>
<P>
But the same official said that there would be no discussions
at the meeting about who would run the Nepals-based southern
command in Europe, an important post traditionally held by an
American general and being demanded by France to be handed over to
an European, in order to make the European Security and Defense
Identity "more visible."
</P>
<P>
As for the external adaptation, the Chiefs of Staff are
expected to examine the issues such as strengthening NATO's
Partnership for Peace program, an update of the military elements
in negotiations with Russia and Ukraine, and the situation in
former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the Chiefs of Staff will also meet with their
counterparts from partner countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
