<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nine More Killed in Communal Clashes in South </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Nine more persons have been killed
in the ethnic clashes in Warri, an oil city in southern Nigeria,
forcing Shell Petroleum Development Company to cut down its crude
oil production there by 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Times reported today that eight persons died on
Sunday night when Kantu, a village of the Itsekiri people, was
torched by unidentified persons.
</P>
<P>
Another young man was killed on Monday as the combatant youths
fired automatic weapons indiscriminately, causing fear and
stampede.
</P>
<P>
Sporadic shootings went on till late last night in parts of
the oil town, said the report.
</P>
<P>
More than a dozen people have been reported dead since the
ethnic crisis broke out between Ijaw and Itsekiri communities
over the relocation of the headquarters of the newly-elected
local government council in late March.
</P>
<P>
The Ijaws also alleged that 44 of their men were killed by the
Itsekiri people.
</P>
<P>
The crisis forced Shell, the biggest foreign oil company
operating in Nigeria, to cut down its production in the area by
15 percent, Shell's General Manager (West) Joshua Udofia
announced on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The company is reported to have lost an estimated 2,000
barrels of crude oil per day since last Saturday when renewed
clashes broke out.  
</P>
</TEXT>
