<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 09:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Hostages in Zaire Pay 250,000 Dollars for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Dozens of Lebanese being held
as hostages in southeastern Zaire are only able to flee a 12-day
ordeal after paying their kidnaper 250,000 U.S. dollars,
local newspaper Daily Star reported today.
</P>
<P>
The only English daily in Lebanon quoted a member of the
Lebanese community in the Zairean capital of Kinshasa as saying
that the hostages Sunday paid the Zairean rebels a total of 250,000
dollars, down from an original demand of 700,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Only identifying himself as Morad, the man said the 46
Lebanese, who were taken as hostages in the city of Mbuji-Mayi on
April 10, had been living under great pressure.
</P>
<P>
"They were under great strain. They were not allowed to make
international phone calls and were confined to the town," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tayseer Fakih, one of the 44 men and two women abducted by
Zairean rebels, said a plane arranged by the British embassy in
Rwanda would arrive in Mbuji-Mayi Tuesday to airlift the hostages
to Johannesburg, a city in the northeastern part of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
"It cost us 60,000 dollars to charter that plane," he said.
</P>
<P>
He criticized the Lebanese government for its handling of the
crisis. "The Lebanese government did nothing. They completely
kept its distance from the issue," Fakih told the newspaper via a
satellite telephone.
</P>
<P>
Haitham Jomaa, Director General of the Lebanese Ministry of
Emigrants, admitted that the government did little to help the
Lebanese captives.
</P>
<P>
"There is no way we could establish contact with the rebel
leader. The only thing we could do was to contact France and
Britain and ask them to help us, and that was what happened," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Fakih confirmed it was only after paying a ransom that the
Lebanese obtained permission from the rebels to leave Mbuji-Mayi.
</P>
<P>
"I do not want to provoke the rebels and jeopardize our
release by revealing the amount we paid," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added the rebels had given them the opportunity to travel
to Goma, the rebel's main headquarters in eastern Zaire, to
prepare papers for their eventual return to Lebanon once the
situation had calmed.
</P>
<P>
Most of some 2,000 Lebanese in Zaire work in the lucrative
diamond business and many have said they will definitely return
whenever possible.
</P>
<P>
Fakih called on the Lebanese government to send a plane to
Johannesburg to take them to Beirut "because we have no more
money left to pay our trip back home."
</P>
<P>
Jomaa said a plane was already waiting in South Africa but
refused to give additional informations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
