<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgarian Foreign Exchange Reserve Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria's foreign exchange
reserve, not including gold reserve, has risen to 1.09 billion
U.S. dollars by April 21, an increase of 536 million dollars over
March 31, the Bulgarian National Bank, the country's central bank,
said today.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time since last January that the country's
foreign exchange had exceeded one billion dollars, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said the growth mainly came from a 180 million
dollar loan by the International Monetary Fund (IMF), a recent
purchase of foreign exchanges worth 200 million dollars and 150
million dollars earned from privatization.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Bulgarian currency, the Lev, has enjoyed a
stable rate against western currencies for a period of time. So
far, it has risen to 1,500 leva against the U.S. dollar since a
sharp devaluation in January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
