<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 09:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Finance Minister Dan Meridor has
expressed support for the granting of exemptions from custom
duties on products manufactured in Jordan by Israeli-Jordanian
joint venture facilities, reported bi-weekly Israel Business
Today.
</P>
<P>
Companies from both countries, including Delta from Israel and
Century from Jordan, have applied to the Israeli government to
consider joint venture products manufactured in Jordan as
Israeli-made goods for the purposes of Israeli custom duty
payments.
</P>
<P>
However, the Ministry of Industry and Trade has objected
to the granting of a full exemption, saying that Israeli
companies which operate in Jordan benefit from lower salary
costs compared with their counterparts which operate in Israel
and help boost employment levels in Israel.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The European Union Commission has decided to
establish a facility in Israel which will focus on economic
cooperation and the promotion of commercial interests of EU
member state business companies in Israel, reported bi-weekly
Israel Business Today.
</P>
<P>
The new unit will be staffed by economists and experts in
a wide range of related fields, in addition to a technical
team. The personnel will manage cooperation projects and locate
business opportunities for EU companies with local service
providers. The unit will also work toward reducing the trade
discrepancy between Israel and the EU.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Israel suffers from an annual trade deficit of
7 billion U.S. dollars and pressure has been applied in
recent years to reduce the gap.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- A group of Israeli companies and university
research institutes has established a research program designed to
enable the development of products based on metallic magnesium,
thereby increasing sales of raw metallic magnesium three-fold,
reported bi-weekly Israel Business Today.
</P>
<P>
At their first meeting, held in the middle of April, the
members of the consortium approved a development budget of 45
million shekels (about 1.4 million U.S. dollar) for the next five
years.
</P>
<P>
The declared aim of the consortium is to arrive at a
situation whereby Israel supplies 12 percent of future products
based on magnesium alloy and the Israeli company, Dead Sea
Works, becomes one of the world's largest suppliers of
magnesium.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The six-member Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC)
states are most likely to fix their unified customs tariffs on
imports at 8 percent, local newspaper Arab Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview published today by the paper, Chief
of Kuwait General Administration of Customs Ibrahim Al-Ghanim
disclosed that GCC Secretary General Jamil al-Hojeilan had
proposed an 8 percent unified tariff, and the member states
considered it as "a suitable meting point."
</P>
<P>
He said that the views of the GCC member states about
unification of customs tariffs had recently become "very close"
after considering the new proposal.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, a regional political and economic organization
founded in 1981, groups Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the United Arab
Emirates, Oman, Qatar and Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
Customs tariffs in the GCC states at present vary from 4
percent to 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
A wide gap existed among the GCC states toward the
unification due to differences in each country's economic
priorities. The disagreement has blocked a tariff agreement
almost since the alliance was formed.
</P>
<P>
GCC's Assistant Secretary General for Economic Affairs Abdulla
Al-Khulaifi said last month that "the major problem is
classification of goods," referring to the three categories of
classification -- goods exempted from tariffs, basic goods with
a tariff of 4 to 8 percent or 8 to 12 percent and other goods.
</P>
<P>
The GCC had finished until recently classifying the last 190
goods and the next step would be to present the list to the GCC
classification committee and the finance ministers in May and
then to the alliance's foreign ministers at their meeting in
June, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
The final authority deciding the issue would be the GCC heads
of state who will hold their annual summit in Kuwait in
December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
