<HEADLINE> South Korea, Belarus to Enhance Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 22 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim
Young-Sam and visiting Belarussian President Alxander Lukashenko
agreed here today to promote bilateral cooperation in trade,
science and technology, and to avoid double taxation.
</P>
<P>
In a bilateral summit meeting held at Presidential Office
Chongwadae, the two leaders exchanged views of common interest,
including the expansion of mutual investment and trade.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders expressed satisfaction with the Korea-Belarus
investment guarantee pact, which was signed by their foreign
ministers following the summit.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to promote bilateral cultural, sports and
tourism exchanges to enhance mutual understanding.
</P>
<P>
Following the summit, South Korean Foreign Minister Yoo
Chong-ha and his Belarussian counterpart Ivan Antonovich signed
the investment guarantee treaty and diplomatic cooperation
protocol in the presence of the two presidents.
</P>
<P>
Under the pact, each government is to provide de facto national
and most-favored nation treatment to businessmen from the other
country in connection with their investment activities.
</P>
<P>
Lukashenko, who arrived here on Monday for a three-day state
visit at the invitation of President Kim, is the first Belarussian
 president to visit Seoul since the two countries established
formal diplomatic ties in February 1992.
</P>
<P>
South Korea exported 18 million U.S. dollars worth of color
television sets, automobiles and electronic products to Belarus
last year and imported six million dollars in integrated circuits
and textiles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
