<DOCNO> XIE19970422.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda to Produce 40,000 Tons of Edibel Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Uganda will produce 40,000
metric tons of edible oil by the year 2000, reported the local
newspaper "the Crusader" today.
</P>
<P>
Otim Odoch, national coordinator of the edible oil producing
companies was quoted as saying that the edible oil industry in
Uganda was producing 40,000 metric tons and was in the process of
expanding production.
</P>
<P>
He said the industry was working with rural farmers to promote
the growth of edible oil producing crops like soya, groundnuts,
simsim and sunflower.
</P>
<P>
Once the targeted production is realised, he said, Uganda will
have enough edible oil for its domestic consumption and a surplus
for export.
</P>
<P>
About 25 years ago, Uganda had sufficient production of edibel
oil to meet domestic demand and some surplus for export to its
neighbouring countries.
</P>
<P>
However, this situation changed adversely after the mass
expulsion of the Asian community by the former president Idi Amin
in 1972. The supply of edible oil began to dwindle away as most
of the oil mills closed down because they were owned by the
departed Asians.
</P>
<P>
This sad situation was further aggravated by the drastic
decline in cotton production that subsequently reduced the supply
of cotton seeds which was a major source of the raw materials for
production of edible oil then. During the political turmoil and
civil war in the 1970s and early 1980s, farmers replaced cotton
farmland with coffee, thus the country's cotton production fell
from a peak of 445,003 bales (one bale equals 185 kilograms) in
1965/66 season to almost zero in 1985.
</P>
<P>
Subsequently, the country can only produce about ten percent
and import nearly 90 percent of the edible oil on the local
market in late 1980s. According to statistics available, the
country was thus subjected to the edible oil scarcity, which
still persists today.
</P>
<P>
During the period from June 1992 to May 1993, Uganda produced
only 2,625 tons of edible oil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
