<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 146 Killed in Road Accidents in Lagos in First </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 22 (Xinhua) -- A total of 146 people, 108 of them
men, were killed in road accidents in Lagos, the biggest city and
economic center of Nigeria, during the first three months of
1997.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Champion reported today that during the period, no
less than 614 accidents involving buses, lorries, taxis, private
cars and motorcycles were recorded, compared with 847 cases a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
A police spokesman was quoted as saying on Monday that 412
persons, including 318 males and 94 females, were injured in the
road clashes between January and March with 1,081 vehicles
involved, compared with 1,130 one year earlier.
</P>
<P>
As the former national capital, Lagos has a well-built road
system which was used by about 288,000 petrol-fired vehicles
spending 7.2 million liters of petrol a day, making for 40
percent of the national daily consumption.
</P>
<P>
Driving without strictly abiding by traffic rules and the poor
conditions of many vehicles are among the major factors causing
road accidents in the city.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
