<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 08:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GCC May Unify Customs Tariffs at 8 Percent: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The six-member Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) states are most likely to fix their
unified customs tariffs on imports at 8 percent, local newspaper
Arab Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview published today by the paper, Chief
of Kuwait General Administration of Customs Ibrahim Al-Ghanim
disclosed that GCC Secretary General Jamil al-Hojeilan had
proposed an 8 percent unified tariff, and the member states
considered it as "a suitable meting point."
</P>
<P>
He said that the views of the GCC member states about
unification of customs tariffs had recently become "very close"
after considering the new proposal.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, a regional political and economic organization
founded in 1981, groups Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the United Arab
Emirates, Oman, Qatar and Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
Customs tariffs in the GCC states at present vary from 4
percent to 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
A wide gap existed among the GCC states toward the
unification due to differences in each country's economic
priorities. The disagreement has blocked a tariff agreement
almost since the alliance was formed.
</P>
<P>
GCC's Assistant Secretary General for Economic Affairs Abdulla
Al-Khulaifi said last month that "the major problem is
classification of goods," referring to the three categories of
classification -- goods exempted from tariffs, basic goods with
a tariff of 4 to 8 percent or 8 to 12 percent and other goods.
</P>
<P>
The GCC had finished until recently classifying the last 190
goods and the next step would be to present the list to the GCC
classification committee and the finance ministers in May and
then to the alliance's foreign ministers at their meeting in
June, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
The final authority deciding the issue would be the GCC heads
of state who will hold their annual summit in Kuwait in
December.
</P>
<P>
Al-Ghanim described the progress in the GCC states' customs
unification efforts as "a great success toward achieving a
strong economic bloc in the face of other international
alliances."
</P>
<P>
He also said the integration of tariffs would have "a
balanced impact" on Kuwait because of its low customs duty which
is only 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
He said Kuwait pays great attention to the unification
issue, believing it would greatly contribute to achieving
economic integration among the GCC states.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he also said Kuwait had decided to delay plans to
raise customs duty on imports to await the unification of
customs tariffs. Kuwait had prepared a study for raising customs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970422.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia to Benefit From Single Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Zambia will benefit from the
establishment of the European Union Common Currency and the
proposed dollar, the single currency of the Common Market for
Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA), a Zambian bank official has
said.
</P>
<P>
Abraham Mwenda, director of financial markets of Bank of
Zambia, said that if the EU comes up with one single
Euro-currency this will make it easy for Zambia to deal with one
currency and help reduce costs, according to Financial Mail.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper today also quoted senior economist with
the bank Jacob Lushinga as saying that the idea of a single
currency is to help facilitate trade and enhance exchange of
goods that could be beneficial to Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Lushinga said the importance of the Euro-currency will depend
on Zambia's major trading partners.
</P>
<P>
The EU is Zambia's second main market for non-traditional
exports after COMESA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970422.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Preparing for Inner Mongolia's 50th Anniversary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The Inner Mongolia Autonomous
Region has been preparing a gala celebration to mark its 50th
anniversary on May 1.
</P>
<P>
Inner Mongolia, which has the majority of China's Mongolian
people, became China's first provincial-level regional autonomous
region when it was established on May 1, 1947.
</P>
<P>
A regional headquarters official in charge of the celebration
activities told reporters that the theme would be "unity,
civilization, opening up, and development" and that it would show
Inner Mongolia's achievements and history, to demonstrate the
success of the regional autonomy system.
</P>
<P>
Because it is in an area of frigid temperatures where, in May,
the new prairie grass has still not had time to grow, the regional
government has decided to start the celebration on July 18, with
activities to last for a month.
</P>
<P>
During that time, a program of honoring role models, a meeting
for 10,000 people, a trade fair, a tourism festival, and many
cultural and entertainment programs will be staged in Hohhot, the
regional capital.
</P>
<P>
The regional party committee and the regional government have
spent 3.13 billion yuan in building 18 major projects for the 50th
anniversary. These include housing programs for teachers in urban
areas, grass-roots health care facilities, cultural facilities,
and power, telecommunications, and transport
facilities. Construction work has been done swiftly and most will
be finished before July, according to local sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
