<HEADLINE> China International Travel Service Expanding Overseas Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The head office of the China
International Travel Service (CITS), the country's largest travel
agency, will sharpen its competitive edge in the overseas tourist
market with more modern telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
Li Lu'an, general manager of the travel service, explained
today at the 46th annual conference of the Pacific Asia Travel
Association (PATA) that it will take the lead in using e-mail as
of May 1 this year, to hook up to major overseas locations via the
network.
</P>
<P>
CITS has joined the Internet and a special cable allows it to
share tourism information with 14 key tourist cities in China, Li
said.
</P>
<P>
CITS is now an agent for many domestic and overseas airlines
and hotels, including Air China, China Eastern, the Wangfujing
Grand Hotel, American Express, and United Airlines.
</P>
<P>
In July of 1995, it joined the International Air Transport
Association (IATA), which consists of airlines from all over the
world, to become its first member on the Chinese mainland, making
ticketing much better.
</P>
<P>
CITS was set up in 1954 and now cooperates with more than 800
travel agents in over 100 countries and regions, and has nine
branch companies overseas. It dealt with 483,000 overseas tourists
in 1996, up 11 percent from the previous year, earning 142 million
US dollars in foreign currency, far exceeding the amount of its
domestic counterparts.
</P>
<P>
PATA, which started in 1952, is an influential non-governmental
tourism organization.  
</P>
</TEXT>
