<HEADLINE> Wild Plant Survey for Northeast China Province Successful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists recently
announced that the Changbai Mountains in Jilin province have a
total of 2,077 types of wild plants after a thorough survey of
materials from two field studies in 1993 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
Changbai Mountains, reputed as a kind of genetic bank for plant
species, are rich in animal and plant resources.
</P>
<P>
With the development of science and technology, more plant
resources will be developed and used to benefit mankind in our
daily lives, scientists say.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed that the mountains boast more than 1,600
kinds of plants, such as grass or trees, that could have
commercial value in medicines, perfumes, and creams.
</P>
<P>
"Natural resources here are well protected, especially 39
species of rare plants," noted Huang Xiangtong, an engineer who
participated in the study. He noted, however, that with an
increase in the illegal digging of rare plants, protection work is
becoming harder.
</P>
<P>
Provincial scientists suggest that a rare plant garden be set
up to provide special meticulous care for those on a brink of
extinction, and more funds are needed for scientific research,
which was recently forced to stop because of a fund shortage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
