<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 08:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Cypriots to Visit Northern Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Around 1,000 Greek Cypriots will
be allowed to visit the Monastery of Apostolos Andreas in the
Turkish-controlled northern part of the island on three
different occasions, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Presidential Commissioner for Humanitarian Issues Takis
Christopoulos was quoted as saying that after arrangements made
by the U.N. in consultation with the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
sides, about 700 Greek Cypriots will be able to visit the
monastery this Sunday to celebrate Greek Orthodox Easter.
</P>
<P>
Other visits are scheduled for August 15, and November
30, two of the most important dates in the Orthodox calendar.
</P>
<P>
These visits came following a visit of more than 400 Turkish
Cypriots to the government-controlled southern part of the
island, for a pilgrimage last Saturday to Hala Sultan Tekke, one
of the holiest Muslim places of worship in the world.
</P>
<P>
Christopoulos expressed the hope that these visits will be the
beginning of continuous communication between the two communities
in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
"We are all ready to work together for a happy and prosperous
Cyprus, for all its inhabitants, regardless of nationality, race
or religion," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that in cooperation with the U.N., he will try to
arrange visits of smaller groups from both communities to
different parts of Cyprus in the future.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government voiced welcome Monday to the
reciprocal visits between the two sides and described them as
desirable development and a good start, which will have
beneficial results on the political effort to find a settlement
in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The exchange of visits were believed here as a result of the
ongoing U.N.-led proximity talks between the Greek and Turkish
Cypriot sides, which began on March 10.
</P>
<P>
The talks were aimed at paving the way for the U.N. proposed
face-to-face negotiations between leaders of the two communities
and getting the two sides to adopt good-will gestures to create
a positive climate for the direct talks.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of a Greek
Cypriot coup seeking union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
