<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 200 Japanese Diet Members Visit Controversial Shrine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 22 (Xinhua) -- More than 200 Diet (Japanese
parliament) members, including two cabinet members, today visited
Yasukuni Shrine where Japanese war dead, including seven class-A
war criminals executed at the end of World War II, are enshrined.
</P>
<P>
Visits to the controversial shrine by senior Japanese officials
have always been criticized by Japan's Asian neighbors which
suffered bitterly under the Japanese militarist heels.
</P>
<P>
On July 29 last year, Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto
visited the shrine, breaking a decade-long taboo on prime
ministerial visit to it and triggering wide-spread condemnation.
</P>
<P>
The 223 Diet members who visited the shrine today, including
Transport Minister Makoto Koga and Director General of Okinawa and
Hokkaido Development Agency Jitsuo Inagaki, belong to a group set
up by the ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) in 1981 for the
purpose of visiting the Shrine.
</P>
<P>
The group was divided into two groups composed of LDP and
non-LDP members following the split of the LDP in 1993. The two
groups were reunited on April 2 this year.
</P>
<P>
The Yasukuni group comprises 228 Diet members -- 184 from the
LDP and 44 from the New Frontier Party (NFP) and other parties.
Former deputy president of the LDP Keizo Obuchi is the chairman of
the group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
