<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central Chinese City Says No To Polluters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Wuhan, the capital of central
China's Hubei Province, has turned down applications for 31
projects in an effort to protect the environment, and recently
vetoed a large chemical project with a proposed investment of 30
million US dollars because of possible pollution of vegetable
fields.
</P>
<P>
This is the latest example of the government's determination to
protect the urban environment of this old industrial base that has
long suffered from severe pollution.
</P>
<P>
The 31 projects were for paper mills, metallurgical and
chemical industries, tanneries, and building materials. Although
the refusal to approval them will cost the city hundreds of millions
of yuan in lost business, the city's environmental protection
bureau thought the move was worthwhile because it could protect
the city from millions of tons of harmful waste discharged by
those industries.
</P>
<P>
The city has also reduced pollution by moving a number of
polluters or by technological renovation. As a result of these
efforts, the quality of the environment in the Qingshan, Hanyang,
and Donghu districts has improved a great deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
