<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Siemens Determined to Regain Past Glory in China  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, April 22 (Xinhua) -- When it comes to business in
China, Siemens of Germany aims high: the electric giant says it is
determined to return to its past glory in China in the 1930s, when
its branch network here was next only to that in Europe.
</P>
<P>
As part of the restoration campaign, Siemens has re-opened a
representative office in Dalian, a coastal city in northeast
China's Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
The re-opening of the office, which was first set up in 1987
but moved to the provincial capital of Shenyang in 1995, has made
Liaoning the second Chinese province in which Siemens has both a
branch and an office. The other is Guangdong Province in the south.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese market is so large that we can't afford to neglect
it," said Hermann J. Koelle, President of Siemens Limited China.
</P>
<P>
He flatly denied that Siemens' business in China, at 2.8
billion marks last year, has peaked. "Our business has just begun
and is at a rising stage," he said.
</P>
<P>
At a ceremony marking the opening of the Dalian office, Koelle
said that Siemens is resolved to grab a big share of the China
market -- and he's confident it will happen.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Li Peng said at the 32nd World Congress of the
International Chamber of Commerce earlier this month that in the
next four years, the China market will be as much as 700 billion
US dollars, which Koelle likened to a "big cake."
</P>
<P>
"We are eyeing the cake and hoping to get a big piece," Koelle
told Xinhua in an interview.
</P>
<P>
Rainer Kordes, Siemens' regional general manager in northeast
China, explained that promising development prospects and business
opportunities in Dalian, one of the first 14 coastal Chinese
cities selected by the central government to open to other parts
of the world, have prompted Siemens to return.
</P>
<P>
The fact that Dalian has become the city with the highest
degree of openness in northeast China and its rapid economic
development and urban construction are other major factors drawing
Siemens back, according to Kordes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970422.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Siemens Determined to Regain Past Glory in China  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"The re-opening of the Dalian office is just one step taken by
Siemens to compete for the northeastern China market," Kordes
said. "We hope it can boost our cooperation with Liaoning and the
entire northeast China."
</P>
<P>
Koelle said Siemens will increase its market share in China by
helping its Chinese partners find answers to funding difficulties,
pledging that the German company will also introduce into China
advanced technology and management.
</P>
<P>
With five branches and 10 offices already in China, Siemens
responded quickly to the Chinese government's strategy to
accelerate development in the central and western parts and to
revamp the old industries in the northeast, by setting up offices
in Chongqing, Chengdu and Dalian.
</P>
<P>
In Liaoning, an industrial base with 10 percent of China's
large and medium-sized state-owned enterprises, China has launched
a multi-billion-dollar program to make over its old industries.
</P>
<P>
Siemens is keen on the business opportunities arising from the
restructuring and rejuvenating, Koelle said.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that more offices will be opened in China, such as
one in Urumqi and more in northeast China.
</P>
<P>
"China is large, and we want to be close to our clients and
stand firm in the market while the competition is still not
fierce," Koelle said.
</P>
<P>
The German company set up a representative office in the
Chinese capital of Beijing in 1982, and signed a memorandum of
understanding with the Chinese government on cooperation in
machinery, electrical equipment and electronics in 1985.
</P>
<P>
Siemens has so far set up 35 joint-funded and cooperative
enterprises and three solely-funded firms in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
