<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North Chinese Hot Springs Cure Ailments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HUHHOT, April 22 (Xinhua) -- People from China and abroad have
been coming to some hot springs at Arxan, a city in north China's
Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region, to get relief for various
ailments.
</P>
<P>
Halun Arxan, which is one of China's five famous springs and
whose name means "hot holy water" in Mongolian, has helped many
people regain their vitality and throw away their walking sticks.
</P>
<P>
One legend has it that during the Qing Dynasty (1616-1911) a
Mongolian Prince went out hunting. When he shot a deer, he sent a
hunter to follow the bloody trail of the wounded animal, but it
disappeared at a spring.
</P>
<P>
He believed that the deer had washed its wound in the spring
and had been cured instantly, and escaped. When he told the prince
about this, the prince became enraged and had the man's thigh
broken and ordered him to wash in the spring to test the
theory. The hunter surprisingly recovered immediately.
</P>
<P>
There are 48 fountains along a 100-ha stretch of grassland,
each one classified according to its ability to help the head, the
feet, the eyes, ears, or stomach, etc. They vary in temperature
from 1 to 50 degrees centigrade.
</P>
<P>
Two of them are the "Mother and Child Springs", only 30 cm
apart but with a temperature difference of 14 degrees. They are
rich in minerals and trace elements, including radioactive
elements, which have proven to have therapeutic effects in nearly
100 different diseases or ailments like arthritis and intestinal
or stomach troubles.
</P>
<P>
The regional government set up a sanatorium in the area in
1954, and electrotherapy, massage, and acupuncture have been added
to make the springs more attractive.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
