<DOCNO> XIE19970422.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Banks Look For Local Professionals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Professionals are much sought
after in Shanghai, as more financial institutions move in, while
the number of existing ones has reached 2,700.
</P>
<P>
Local news media carry a large number of ads to offer jobs in
banks, insurance companies, and securities firms with good
salaries, promotion prospects, and overseas training opportunities.
</P>
<P>
About 90 percent of the positions require a bachelor's degree
at the minimum, and 40 percent a doctorate or a master's degree.
</P>
<P>
To meet the growing market demand, a dozen local universities
now offer degrees in finance and graduate more than 3,000 students
annually. Many graduates with degrees in finance from other parts
of the country have come to hunt jobs in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
One local expert notes that, while the number of professionals
is now sufficient to meet the general demands of the local
financial sector, industry is still experiencing a severe shortage
of top-flight personnel, especially those good at analytic work,
management, and administrative affairs.
</P>
<P>
"Whenever an employee has his monthly salary raised to 10,000 yuan
or more, head-hunters start flocking around him," said a credit
officer with a foreign bank.
</P>
<P>
Yoshiaki Kawamata, Diretor of Sanwa Bank's Shanghai Branch,
told Xinhua that it normally takes five years to train
senior bank personnel and 10 years a branch manager, but in
Shanghai, foreign banks have had to cut the training period by
half.
</P>
<P>
There are now more than 200 overseas banking institutions in
Shanghai and most would rather hire Chinese nationals who are
more familiar with local laws, have better contacts, and demand
less pay.
</P>
<P>
"The headquarters of my bank wants us to employ more local
people," Mr. Kawamata said, while admitting that it is not very
easy to do so. He pointed out that some local staff members have
left for foreign countries after years of training on the job,
which has had a negative effect on the local banking industry.
</P>
<P>
Eight foreign banks have been approved by the People's Bank of
China to open branches in the city's Pudong New Area to deal in
RMB. They are likely to hire more professionals for the new
business. This will mean a new round of searching for skillful
people among local banks, observers said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
