<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ to Deregulate Mail Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand government
introduced a bill in the parliament this afternoon which will
deregulate the post service, the last monopoly in the country.
</P>
<P>
The legislation, the Postal Service Bill, will do away with the
sole right to deliver ordinary letters enjoyed by New Zealand
Post, a state-owned enterprise which Communication Minister
Maurice Williamson described as a good company.
</P>
<P>
The deregulation will allow the private sector to set up post
offices and deliver mail. New operators will also be able to set
up public letterboxes.
</P>
<P>
Williamson argued that the competition will benefit the
customers.
</P>
<P>
"So all and all, I think if we can see the benefits many other
industries have achieved for the consumers with competition coming
into play, rates have dropped and services have increased. Courier
companies for many years have complaints they are traveling around
the city, picking up parcels and picking up other things while
they cannot pick up the standard letter."
</P>
<P>
However, leader of the opposition Labor Party, Helen Clark, was
critical of the bill, seeing it as a sign of privatization of New
Zealand Post.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
