<DOCNO> XIE19970422.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: A Conspicuous Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The Washington summit on Friday
between the United States and Japan on the defense situation in
the Asia-Pacific region will focus on U.S. military bases in Japan
and the Japanese-U.S. security mechanism.
</P>
<P>
The summit, between Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto
and U.S. President Bill Clinton, will be of particular
significance in that it will coordinate their stances on military
cooperation and enhance their military alliance, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto has threatened to expand the scope of Japan-U.S.
defense cooperation to include China's Taiwan Province and Nansha
Islands, introducing a dangerous note into the summit, according
to the analysts.
</P>
<P>
It is well known that over recent years, Japan and the
U.S. have been trying to position their alliance ready for the
21st century and have taken practical measures to strengthen the
alliance.
</P>
<P>
At their Tokyo summit in April last year, Hashimoto and Clinton
reassessed the Treaty of Mutual Cooperation and Security between
Japan and the U.S. signed in 1960, and reached consensus on
expanding the scope of Japan-U.S. defense cooperation.
</P>
<P>
At this week's summit, they are expected to discuss the
problems they are facing in enhancing military cooperation in the
Asia-Pacific region, and to implement the agreement reached in
military cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The two sides faced two major stumbling blocks in strengthening
their military cooperation -- the issue of U.S. military bases in
Japan's Okinawa Prefecture, and modification of the 1978
Guidelines for U.S.-Japan Defense Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The first issue was resolved earlier this month after the
Japanese government, in spite of strong opposition from Okinawan
residents and in accordance with U.S. wishes, provided land for
U.S. military facilities -- a "gift" for Japan to bring to the
summit table.
</P>
<P>
Now, with the land issue settled, modifying the guidelines for
cooperation has been placed on the agenda and is a core issue of
the summit this month.
</P>
<P>
The aim of modifying the guidelines is clear -- to expand the
scope of Japan-U.S. defense cooperation to cover the whole of the
Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto has barely been able to conceal his enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting of cadres of the political affairs investigation
committee of Japan's ruling Liberal Democratic Party, he said
flagrantly that when modifying the guidelines, (he and Clinton)
would take into consideration not only possible "trouble" on the
Korean Peninsula but also "trouble" regarding China's Nansha
Islands and Taiwan Province, Nihon Hoso Kyokai (NHK) television
reported on April 9.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese newspapers did not report Hashimoto's remarks, but
the message he intends giving Clinton on the scope of
Japan-U.S. defense cooperation is obvious.
</P>
<P>
It is not accidental that Hashimoto has listed China's Taiwan
and Nansha Islands as being on the periphery of Japan's defense
area. This is closely connected with the dangerous trends emerging
in Japanese society in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Although World War Two ended over half a century ago, the ghost
of militarism still haunts Japan, and some leading politicians in
the country time and again want to reverse the nature of the war
of aggression, in which Japan inflicted tremendous suffering on
the people of Asia.
</P>
<P>
In July last year, Hashimoto, in the capacity of prime
minister, paid homage to the Yasukuni Shrine housing the memorial
tablets of 14 class-A war criminals. His action has helped spread
the trend of right-wing thought in Japan.
</P>
<P>
As a result, some right-wingers undisguisedly went to China's
Diaoyu Islands last year to create trouble, and certain people
with ulterior motives even claimed that China was Japan's "threat."
</P>
<P>
It is against such a background, that Hashimoto, as prime
minister, has openly sought to include China's Taiwan and Nansha
Islands in Japanese-U.S. defense cooperation.
</P>
<P>
His intentions are obvious. As the Chinese saying goes, "Sima
Zhao's ill intent is known to all -- the villain's design is
obvious." Such a tendency cannot but make people vigilant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970422.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CDU Central Council Endorses Kohl's Bid for Chancellorship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 21 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl's bid
to run for an unprecedented fifth term in next year's general
election was unanimously endorsed by the central council of his
Christian Democratic Union (CDU) party here today.
</P>
<P>
But his bid still needs final approval by the party's national
congress due in mid-October.
</P>
<P>
Defying opinion polls showing that a majority of Germans want
him to retire from politics, Kohl announced on April 2 that after
15 years as chancellor, he felt a personal duty to run for a fifth
term while Germany was facing challenges at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
Having secured a place in history as the architect of German
reunification, Kohl obviously still has ambitions to play a major
role in pushing forward the European integration process,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believe that Kohl's campaign announcement also served
a political purpose -- to put pressure on the main opposition
Social Democratic Party (SPD) -- to choose its candidate for
chancellor, a move which could lead to SDP's internal power
struggles.
</P>
<P>
However, the SPD, which currently has at least three possible
candidates, has made clear that it won't decide until early next
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
