<HEADLINE> Colombian President Arrives For Andean Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Colombian President
Ernesto Samper arrived in Sucre, Bolivia, today for a summit of
the presidents of the Andean Group nations to discuss the future
of regional integration.
</P>
<P>
The presidents of Venezuela, Ecuador and Bolivia will also
attend the summit.
</P>
<P>
During the flight, President Samper told reporters that the
presidents will demonstrate that the Andean Group will remain
vigorous in spite of Peru's decision to withdraw from the regional
integration process.
</P>
<P>
Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori announced on April 12 that
his country would leave the Andean Group after its free-trade
proposals were rejected by the four other member countries.
</P>
<P>
In early April, Peru proposed eliminating subsidies and other
measures to boost free and fair trade in the region.
</P>
<P>
Samper said that they should not lose hope that Peru will
reconsider its position in the next few months.
</P>
<P>
The old Andean Group, established in May 1969, is to be renamed
the Andean Community and Samper said the change would be
accompanied by "a new integration scheme to show the community is
stronger than ever."
</P>
<P>
Samper said that during the summit, he and his Venezuelan
counterpart Rafael Caldera will holds talks on patrolling the
hundreds of kilometers of their common border. 
</P>
</TEXT>
