<HEADLINE> Austria, Greece Urge Europe to Consider Small Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Austrian and Greek leaders today
called for the European Union (EU) to secure the voice and the
interests of small members in the bloc's structural reform.
</P>
<P>
Followiing their meeting, Austrian Federal Chancellor Viktor
Klima and visiting Greek Prime Minister Constantinos Simitis said
the new EU treaty to be adopted at a summit in June should take
account of the concerns of small countries.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Simitis arrived at Vienna today on a three-day
visit. He said the two countries shared views on Europe's common
foreign and security policies.
</P>
<P>
He said Greece supported Austria's right to decide whether or
not to take part in the European defense mechanism.
</P>
<P>
France, Germany and Italy, eager to accelerate the European
integration, have proposed that the new EU treaty includes the
creation of an EU defense structure, bringing the Western European
Union into the bloc. Britain and the neutral member states have
opposed the proposal.
</P>
<P>
On the situation in volatile Albania, Simitis said the EU
should pay more attention to the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also agreed that the EU treaty include reform
in employment. The 15-nation EU is suffering from an average
jobless rate of over 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
They said the launching date and the criteria of the EU
monetary union should be observed.
</P>
<P>
Simitis said although Greece could not be able to qualify for
admission into the single currency in the first group, it would
try its best to join as one of the second group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
