<HEADLINE> Peru's Withdrawal From Andean Group Regretted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SUCRE, BOLIVIA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The Andean Group of South
American countries is lamenting the decision by the Peruvian
government to withdraw from the subregional bloc.
</P>
<P>
A document, known as the Sucre Act, will be signed by four
presidents of the Andean Group at the ninth Andean Presidential
Council here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It said in its second paragraph that Peru's move violated the
essential principles and values of the world economy which favors
developing and enhancing economic blocs.
</P>
<P>
Peru's decision deprives the Andean Group of a partner and
adversely affects the economic integration process in the region,
the act says.
</P>
<P>
Peru decided recently to quit membership of the Andean Group
unless the other four members -- Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador and
Venezuela -- stopped pressing it to reduce its customs duties to
zero.
</P>
<P>
Peru also accused those members, which had already introduced
the duty-free policy, of providing subsidies to their export
products to Peru.
</P>
<P>
The future trade ties between Peru and other member states will
be a major topic of the forthcoming summit.
</P>
<P>
The Sucre Act hoped Peru would rejoin the Andean Group in the
future.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Act called for preserving, as much as possible,
the channels for developing ties between the Andean Group and Peru.
</P>
<P>
The governments of Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador and Venezuela
declare their unfailing pledge to continue working towards the
integration.
</P>
<P>
The Andean Group will be named as the Andean Community after
the summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
