<HEADLINE> Thailand, Bangladesh Move to Strengthen Trade Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Thailand and Bangladesh have
agreed to expand their economic cooperation through creating joint
ventures in more new areas with a trade target of 400 million U.S.
dollars set by 2000, reports reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
The new areas will cover fishery, poultry, textiles, dyeing and
chemicals, food processing, leather, footwear, plastics and
tourism.
</P>
<P>
Thai Deputy Foreign Minister Pitak Intrawityanunt said Monday
that details of the cooperation will be discussed at the next
Thai-Bangladesh Joint Commission meeting scheduled in Bangkok
later this year.
</P>
<P>
Thailand and Bangladesh had enjoyed close and cordial relations
since they established diplomatic ties in 1972, but the potential
of their economic relations has not been fully tapped, Pitak said.
</P>
<P>
With a population of 125 million, Bangladesh provided a vast
market for joint investments such as in the production of
high-quality and low-cost consumer products for its domestic
market, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The opportunities are also seen for joint investments in
Bangladesh in the production of textiles, processed foods,
electronics for exports to the developed world as well as joint
exploration and utilization of energy resources, he added.
</P>
<P>
Thailand and Bangladesh signed a treaty earlier this month to
avoid double taxation to pay the way for their cooperation in the
field of joint investment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
