<HEADLINE> Nepal's Largest Party Issues Manifesto for Local Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's largest political party
has released its manifesto for the upcoming local elections and
predicted a landslide victory for itself in the polls.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party of Nepal (United Marxist Leninist, CPN-UML)
in the manifesto, which was made public Monday, called for voters'
support to the party in order to make local administrative bodies
more people-oriented.
</P>
<P>
"Voting for other parties means institutionalizing corruption
for another term of five years," it said.
</P>
<P>
A landslide victory of CPN-UML in the coming local elections
would be a necessity for political stability and local bodies'
empowerment in the country, the CPN-UML manifesto said.
</P>
<P>
The CPN-UML, a major partner of Prime Minister Lokendra Bahadur
Chand's three-party government, wants to gain more control over
the country's 4,000 local bodies through the local elections
scheduled for next month.
</P>
<P>
Currently the main opposition the Nepali Congress (NC) controls
most of local bodies in the country at the village, municipality
and district levels.
</P>
<P>
The NC party, the second largest party with almost same
strength as the CPN-UML in the hung parliament, announced its
local election manifesto Saturday with a view to maintaining its
overwhelming control of local authorities.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Prime Minister Chand has been touring the country
since last weekend to meet with local people and workers of his
National Democratic Party (RPP) as part of the party's campaign
for the elections.  
</P>
</TEXT>
