<HEADLINE> Ukrainian Considers Self-supporting Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma on
Monday approved an economic concept which clearly divides the
military forces into combat forces and service forces -- the
latter providing funds for the combat forces.
</P>
<P>
Valery Muntyan, director of the Economic Bureau of the Defense
Ministry, said that the concept provided for the service forces
making money for the military coffers without using a penny of the
government's money.
</P>
<P>
Muntyan noted that the combat sector would be separate from the
service sector. The service sector would include work forces,
military plants, etc., and would employ redundant personnel and
equipment only to make money.
</P>
<P>
He believed the concept would provide 8 percent of the military
budget by the end of 1997 and 20 percent a year later.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Ministry has 46 enterprises now, eight of which are
ready to make and repair jeeps. Muntyan expected these present and
future factories could make billions of U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian government allocated 1.45 billion hryvnas (about
797 million U.S. dollars) to its armed forces this year, but this
meets only 36 percent of the military's needs.
</P>
<P>
The concept could solve Ukraine's financial crisis, the
official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970422.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lending Growth Slows Down in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Lending growth by Thailand's
commercial banks was slowing down in the first quarter of this
year, averaging 0.73 percent per month over the same period last
year, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The loans offered by local commercial banks posted 4,124
billion baht (164.96 billion U.S. dollars) in January, 4,170
billion baht (166.8 billion dollars) in February, and 4,184
billion baht (167.36 billion dollars) in March.
</P>
<P>
One of the main factors attributing to the slowdown was low
savings. The lending currently is 1.4 times the savings in
commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
Local commercial banks reported average savings growth of 1.18
percent in the first three months of this year, with savings
totaling 3,620 billion baht (144.8 billion dollars) in January,
3,670 billion baht (146.8 billion dollars) in February, 3,710
billion baht (148.4 billion dollars) in March.
</P>
<P>
Commercial banks are finding their hands tied. Although they
hope to maintain the growth of lending, a major source of their
revenues, they cannot afford bad loans.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
