<HEADLINE> Beijing to Issue Discount Cards to 80,000 People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Beijing's 80,000 retirees and
laid-off workers are to enjoy discounts at designated grocers,
babers and repair shops, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
"This group of people are expected to increasingly rely on
society instead of their work units," said Xu Xiaoyu, head of
social welfare with the Beijing Labor Bureau.
</P>
<P>
About 59,000 cards promising preference and discounts were sent
out last year for the first time.
</P>
<P>
Community volunteers, mostly from local middle schools and
colleges, worked to obtain shopping, hairdressing and repair shop
discounts for card holders.
</P>
<P>
Open to all residents, the volunteer groups also went around
their neighborhoods recruiting laid-off workers and retirees into
the card discount programme.
</P>
<P>
The number of these groups will expand from 32 to 50 this year,
Xu said.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Labour Bureau estimate more than 200,000 workers
will be out of work by the end of this year, as compared to
110,000 at the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
In Dongzhimen, dongcheng District, a small grocer's which sells
2,000 kinds of goods offers five percent discounts to the
cardholders.
</P>
<P>
Almost 2,000 card-carrying retirees and laid-off workers
patronize the shop. They account for 70 percent of its total
customers .
</P>
<P>
There will be two new stores this year in Dongcheng, where
there are 50,000 retirees, said Lin Zhaolu, vice manager of the
group.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the municipal government has earmarked more than 10
million yuan (1.2 million US dollars) in training 8,500 laid-off
workers at vocational schools. 
</P>
</TEXT>
