<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Background: ABCs of Basic Law of Hong Kong SAR (37-38) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Following are the ABCs of the
Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (37-38)
in a question-and-answer format:
</P>
<P>
Question: What kind of a body is the Legislative Council of the
Hong Kong SAR?
</P>
<P>
Answer: The Legislative Council of the Hong Kong SAR is the
legislature of the Hong Kong SAR. Its functions are: to enact,
amend or repeal laws in accordance with legal procedures; to
examine and approve budgets introduced by the government; to
approve taxation and public expenditure; to receive and debate the
policy addresses of the Chief Executive; to raise questions on the
work of the government; to debate any issue concerning public
interests; to endorse the appointment and removal of the judges
of the Court of Final Appeal and the Chief Judge of the High
Court; to receive and handle complaints from Hong Kong residents;
and to pass a motion of impeachment of the Chief Executive and
report it to the central government for decision.
</P>
<P>
The Legislative Council of the Hong Kong SAR is fundamentally
different from the British Hong Kong Legislative Council. The
latter was established in accordance with British royal
instructions and has acted only as an advisory body for the
governor in the enactment of laws.
</P>
<P>
The Legislative Council of the Hong Kong SAR, to be established
in accordance with the Basic Law and relevant decisions of the
People's Congress, will be a legislature with the power to enact,
amend and repeal laws.
</P>
<P>
Question: How will the Legislative Council of the Hong Kong SAR
be constituted, and what qualifications must council members meet?
</P>
<P>
Answer: It will be constituted by election. The method for
forming the Legislative Council will be specified in the light of
the actual situation in the Hong Kong SAR and in accordance with
the principle of gradual and orderly progress.
</P>
<P>
The specific method for forming the Legislative Council and its
procedures for voting on bills and motions are prescribed in Annex
2 of the Basic Law. The ultimate aim is the election of all
members of the Legislative Council by universal suffrage.
</P>
<P>
The Legislative Council will be composed of Chinese citizens
who are permanent residents of the regions with no right of abode
in any foreign country.
</P>
<P>
However, permanent residents of the region who are not of
Chinese nationality may also be elected members of the Legislative
Council, provided that the proportion of such members does not
exceed 20 percent of the total membership of the Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970422.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Offers Aid to Thai Plastic Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Japan will offer a fund of 10
million baht (400,000 U.S. dollars) to help the Thai plastic
industry conduct research and development.
</P>
<P>
The fund is to be offered by the Japanese International Trade
and Industry Ministry mainly to help the Thai engineering plastics
sector develop easy-forming technology, according to the
Department of Industrial Promotion under the Thai Commerce
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The assistance will cover three years and be provided in the
form of machinery, while Japan will send experts to help train
Thai specialists, the department said.
</P>
<P>
According to data from the department, Thailand's consumption
of engineering plastics reached 50,000 tons in 1996, up 15 percent
from the previous year. The consumption is expected to climb up to
100,000 tons by 2007. 
</P>
</TEXT>
