<DOCNO> XIE19970422.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fund Helps Tibetans Recover Eyesight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Living on the Qinghai-Tibet
Plateau, the Tibetan people receive the world's strongest exposure
to ultraviolet rays from the sun.
</P>
<P>
As a result, cataracts have become a widespread eye illness for
Tibetan people who have weaker eyesight or even lose their
eyesight.
</P>
<P>
Their suffering has aroused great concern from the Tibet
Development Fund (TDF), China's first non-governmental charity
organization in the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau, today's China Daily
said.
</P>
<P>
The TDF is focusing its 1997 charity efforts on helping Tibetan
cataract patients recover their eyesight.
</P>
<P>
According to Ngapo Jigyuan, deputy secretary-general of TDF,
the organization is preparing to set up an eye-care center this
year in the capital city of Lhasa to train opthalmologists to
treat cataract patients.
</P>
<P>
He said they are now seeking international assistance and have
held talks with some international charity organizations on the
matter.
</P>
<P>
Ngapo Jigyuan, also director of TDF's Beijing Branch Office,
said three foreign organizations have agreed to send medical teams
to China to treat Tibetan cataract patients in July-September of
this year in three Tibetan ethnic areas.
</P>
<P>
The three areas will be Ali and Nagchu prefectures of Tibet and
Ganzi prefecture of Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
Nagchu prefecture has a population of about 300,000 and there
are now more than 15,000 cataract patients.
</P>
<P>
Because of the higher level of ultraviolet rays and poor living
standards of many Tibetan patients, the number of cataract
patients in Naqu is still growing by about 1,000 each year.
</P>
<P>
Jigyuan said medical experts sent by Seva Foundation of the
United States, Foundation Eye Care Himalaya of the Netherlands and
Nepal Eye Program of Nepal will conduct eye operations on some 600
Tibetan cataract patients in each prefecture during the period,
using high-quality imported and artificially produced crystalline
lenses.
</P>
<P>
Many Tibetan cataract patients used to be major food earners
for their families. But the eye disease results in deteriorating
living standards as they lose their labor abilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
