<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinjiang Traders Expect 50 million US Dollars at Trade Fair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Traders from Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region are expected to notch up deals worth 50 million
US dollars at the ongoing 81st Chinese Export Commodities Fair in
Guangzhou, capital of south China's Guangdong Province, today's
"China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based newspaper quoted Yang Zhongfeng, deputy
director general of the Bureau of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation of Xinjiang as saying that they clinched deals worth
15 million US dollars in the first six days of the spring fair,
and expected this amount to more than treble by the end of the
event.
</P>
<P>
At the fair, Yang urged traders from his region to grain
invaluable modern business techniques and gather commercial
information while bidding for export contracts.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of 1997, foreign trade in the region hit
320 million US dollars, up 54 percent from a year ago. Exports
grew 109 percent to 180 million US dollars, creating a trade
surplus of 40 million US dollars. Foreign trade each month rose
more than 50 percent above the same month last year.
</P>
<P>
The central government aims to invest 12 billion US dollars in
Xinjiang during the 1996-2000 period. Xinjiang lags behind some
other provinces in terms of capital and technology. On the other
hand, it has geological advantages.
</P>
<P>
Along its 5,400-kilometer-long border, there are 15 entry
points connecting the region with eight countries. Over-the-border
trade accounts for 50 percent of the region's foreign trade total.
</P>
<P>
Vast grasslands in Xinjiang benefit the animal husbandry
industry. Xinjiang is rich in mineral resources. More than 130
varieties of minerals have been found.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang's potential oil supply, believed to be second only to
that in the Gulf, is coveted by oil companies around the world,
the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
