<DOCNO> XIE19970422.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Briefs from Southern Common Market Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Following are news briefs from
the Southern Common Market countries in the past few days.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- The Southern Common Market (Mercosur) countries
will reach a monetary unification in 15 years and this system will
be a response to the macro-economic challenges in the bloc, said a
recent report by Brazil's National Economic and Social Development
Bank.
</P>
<P>
The unification will require the deficit in all of the member
nations to be below 2.5 percent of their gross domestic product
(GDP), debts not to exceed 40 percent of the GDP and inflation be
less than 4 percent before the year 2006.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentine and Brazilian Presidents Carlos Menem
and Henrique Cardoso will meet in Rio de Janeiro on April 26-27 to
analyze matters on economy, border, security and international
defense.
</P>
<P>
LA PAZ -- The Confederation of Private Enterprises in Bolivia
(CEPB) maintains that the Andean Community should orientate its
efforts to joining the Mercosur trade bloc to form a united South
American bloc.
</P>
<P>
This position is backed by public figures from various sectors
saying that Bolivia can perform a much more important role because
of its location as a transport hub between Atlantic and Pacific
coasts.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Exports from small and medium Argentine
companies to Brazil fell by 30 percent due to the financing
restrictions on imports imposed by Brazil.
</P>
<P>
According to the General Economic Confederation, the drop was
resulted from Argentine exporters' refusal to lower their prices
of 5-7 percent requested by their Brazilian customers to maintain
trade relations.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Different universities will give a course
"Business Administration Program: Mercosur and International
Markets" in Montevideo on April 24.
</P>
<P>
This course will provide theoretical and instrumental knowledge
for executives of the markets of the region. The program will end
in December.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Argentina, Uruguay and Paraguay will ask Brazil
to suspend the restrictions that affect Brazilian imports from
their countries on August 1.
</P>
<P>
Their petition will be presented during the meeting of economy
minister and central bank presidents to be held in Asuncion on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Uruguayan Economy Minister Luis Mosca said he was optimistic
about a solution to the problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
