<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chronology: Sino-Russian Contacts Since 1992 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
pays a five-day state visit to Russia beginning Tuesday at the
invitation of his Russian counterpart, Boris Yeltsin. It is the
fourth official summit between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Sino-Russian relations of good-neighborliness, friendship and
mutually-beneficial cooperation have been strengthened and
deepened, as shown by the frequent exchange of visits by leaders
of the two countries since the disintegration of the former Soviet
Union in December 1991.
</P>
<P>
The following is a chronology of high-level contacts between
China and Russia from 1992 to 1996:
</P>
<P>
1992:
</P>
<P>
January 31: Chinese Premier Li Peng met with Russian President
Boris Yeltsin during a summit meeting of the United Nations
Security Council. Both pledged to strengthen cooperation and
contacts.
</P>
<P>
March 15-17: Russian Foreign Minister Andrei Kozirev visited
China.
</P>
<P>
November 24-26: Chinese State Councillor and Foreign Minister
Qian Qichen visited Russia.
</P>
<P>
December 17-19: Russian President Yeltsin paid his first visit
to China. The two sides issued a joint communique on the
foundation of bilateral relations. Both agreed it was in the
fundamental interests of the two peoples and was conducive to
peace and stability in Asia and the whole world to further
strengthen and develop bilateral relations. They vowed to develop
relations of good-neighborliness and mutually-beneficial
cooperation, in accordance with the U.N. Charter, the Five
Principles of Peaceful Coexistence (mutual respect for territorial
integrity and sovereignty, mutual non-aggression, non-interference
in each other's internal affairs, equality and mutual benefit, and
peaceful co-existence) and other established principles of
international law. The two sides signed a number of agreements on
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
1993:
</P>
<P>
January 12-19: A delegation of the Russian Supreme Soviet
visited China.
</P>
<P>
June 23-July 5: Vice Chairman of China's Central Military
Commission Liu Huaqing, heading a government delegation, visited
Russia.
</P>
<P>
November 8-11: Russian Defense Minister Pavel Grachev visited
China.
</P>
<P>
1994:
</P>
<P>
January 27-29: Russian Foreign Minister Andrei Kozirev visited
China.
</P>
<P>
May 14-18: Russian Duma (lower house of parliament) Speaker
Ivan Rybkin visited China.
</P>
<P>
May 26-29: Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin visited
China.
</P>
<P>
The two sides signed seven agreements. Chinese President Jiang
Zemin, at a meeting with Chernomyrdin, said the two countries
should consider and handle bilateral relations from a strategic
point of view with an eye on the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
June 27-29: Chinese Vice Premier and Foreign Minister Qian
Qichen visited Russia.
</P>
<P>
July 11-16: Chinese Defense Minister Chi Haotian visited
Russia.
</P>
<P>
September 2-6: President Jiang Zemin paid an official visit to
Russia and signed a joint declaration with President Boris
Yeltsin. They hailed the development of bilateral relations since
the 1992 summit and pointed out that it was time to establish a
new constructive partnership between the two countries. They also
signed a number of other documents, including an agreement on
de-targeting nuclear weapons at each other, on laying legal
foundations for Sino-Russian relations for the next century and
one on defining the western boundary of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
1995:
</P>
<P>
May 7-9: President Jiang Zemin visited Moscow to attend
celebrations marking the 50th anniversary of the victory of the
Anti-Fascist War. Jiang and his Russian counterpart, Boris
Yeltsin, agreed to strengthen the long-term relationship of good
neighborliness and friendship based on mutually beneficial
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
June 25-28: Premier Li Peng paid an official visit to Moscow
and held talks with his Russian counterpart, Viktor Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
The two signed a Sino-Russian joint communique praising the
goal set by both sides for developing a long-term and stable
relationship of good neighborliness, friendship and cooperation of
mutual benefit between the two countries, with the 21st century in
perspective. Li also met with President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
December 2-9: Liu Huaqing, vice chairman of the Central
Military Commission, visited Moscow as head of a government
delegation.
</P>
<P>
1996:
</P>
<P>
March 31-April 5: Qiao Shi, chairman of the National People's
Congress Standing Committee, paid an official visit to Russia.
</P>
<P>
Qiao met with Russian President Boris Yeltsin, Prime Minister
Viktor Chernomyrdin and chairmen of both houses of the Russian
parliament.
</P>
<P>
April 24-26: Russian President Boris Yeltsin visited China.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin and Yeltsin signed a joint
statement announcing their resolve to develop a strategic
coordination partnership of equality and mutual confidence
oriented toward the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
April 26: Presidents of China, Russia, Kazakstan, Kyrgyzstan
and Tajikistan signed an agreement on confidence-building in the
military field in border areas.
</P>
<P>
September 20-26: Li Ruihuan, chairman of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference, paid an official good-will
visit to Russia. Li held talks with Russian Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin and chairmen of both houses of the Russian parliament.
</P>
<P>
October 21-24: Chairman of the Russian Federation Council
(upper house of parliament) Yegor Stroyev visited China.
</P>
<P>
November 17-19: Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov
visited China.
</P>
<P>
December 9-13: A Russian government delegation, headed by
First Deputy Prime Minister Alexei Bolyshakov, visited China.
</P>
<P>
December 26-28: Premier Li Peng paid a three-day working visit
to Russia at the invitation of his Russian counterpart, Viktor
Chernomyrdin. It marked the official start of regular meetings
between premiers of the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970422.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
