<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Rice Exports Plummet in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Thai rice export volume posted
1.04 million tons in the first quarter of this year, slumping by
about 30.2 percent compared with the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the Rice Exporters Association, some 60 percent of
the rice exported in the period was high-grade rice, especially
fragrant rice.
</P>
<P>
The surging price of Thai rice on the world market was among
the main factors contributing to the slump, the association said.
</P>
<P>
The value of Thai rice exports posted 10.813 billion baht
(432.5 million U.S. dollars), dropping some 16.8 percent from the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Local rice exporters doubt that the situation will improve in
the second quarter as the prices of Thai rice remain high with
fragrant rice now being sold at more than 700 U.S. dollars a ton.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines is expected to import at least 250,000 tons of
Thai rice and will be the largest export market for Thai rice,
according to the association.
</P>
<P>
Iran hoped to import about 400,000 tons of Thai rice and it had
already bought 100,000 tons, the association said. However, the
Thai government is wary of signing any deal with Iran, as the
country's quality inspections are too strict, it added.
</P>
<P>
China has signed a memorandum of understanding to buy 1.03
million tons of rice from Thailand and 70 to 80 percent of the
purchase will be fragrant rice, the association said.
</P>
<P>
To reach this year's rice export target of 5.3 million tons,
Somboon Pathaichan, manager of the association, pointed out that
Thai rice exporters would have to step up marketing efforts and
push for exports of low-grade rice.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970422.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
