<HEADLINE> Czech, Russia Ready to Develop Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
PRAGUE, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The Czech and Russian prime
ministers expressed willingness to develop bilateral relations,
despite differences of principles over the planned eastwards
expansion of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
At their talks here on Monday, Czech Prime Minister Vaclav
Klaus and his visiting Russian counterpart, Viktor Chernomyrdin,
said there was a particular willingness to develop economic
relations.
</P>
<P>
The two prime ministers told a joint press conference after
the talks that they decided to further promote economic
cooperation and trade, and set up joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
The Czech Republic and Russia signed two agreements Monday on
cooperation. One was over fighting organized crime and the other
about Russia paying back debts to the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin began his three-day visit to the Czech Republic
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Prague, Chernomyrdin met with Milos Zeman,
Chairman of the Chamber of Deputies, and Petr Pithart, Chairman of
the Senate, respectively exchanging views on international issues
and furthering bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin met Monday night with representatives from Czech
businesses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
