<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Justice Minister Resigns to Work Against President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Colombia's Justice
Minister Carlos Medellin resigned today in order to work for a
major critic of President Ernesto Samper.
</P>
<P>
Medellin told a news conference that he was stepping down to
work on the presidential campaign of Carlos Lleras de la Fuente.
</P>
<P>
Carlos Lleras, who was the son of former president Carlos
Lleras Restrepo, resigned as Colombia's ambassador to Washington
last year amid allegations that Samper used drug money to finance
his 1994 election campaign.
</P>
<P>
He has announced that he would run for the presidency in 1998,
and has openly criticised President Samper since he left his
ambassadorial post.
</P>
<P>
Samper said he regretted the move but accepted the
resignation. He has named his legal counsellor, Alma Beatriz
Rengifo de Estrada, as the new justice minister.
</P>
<P>
Medellin was in Washington's graces for his determination to
push harsh anti-drug laws through parliament and his firm support
for lifting the country's constitutional ban on extradition.
</P>
