<HEADLINE> Arianespace to Launch Indonesia's Telkom I Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia has designated Europe's
Arianespace to launch a new satellite of the state-owned
telecommunication company Pt. Telkom by early 1999, official
sources here said today.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed here Monday, Arianespace, which
launched Indonesia's Palapa C-2 telecommunication satellite in May
1996, will launch the Telkom I satellite, built by U.S. firm
Lockheed Martin Communication Corporation, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
The 2,500 kilogram Telkom I will have 32 c-band transponders
and will accommodate the company's needs for voice and data
transfer for more than 15 years.
</P>
<P>
The value of the contract was not given but industry sources
estimated the cost at up to 140 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Telkom officials said that the new satellite, expected to be
launched from the European spaceport in French Guyana, will
replace the Palapa B2r which is scheduled to end its service life
in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has four Palapa telecommunication satellites in
orbit, three of the B generation and one of the C series.
</P>
<P>
An archipelago of more than 13,000 islands, Indonesia depends
largely on rocket-launched satellite for telecommunications.
</P>
</TEXT>
