<HEADLINE> ASEAN Mission Studies Myanmar's Preparation for Entry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 22 (Xinhua) -- An 18-member fact-finding mission
is now here studying Myanmar's preparation for membership of the
Association of Southeast-Asian Nations (ASEAN).
</P>
<P>
The mission, which comprises officials of ASEAN
secretary-general's office, called on Myanmar Minister for
National Planning and Economic Development Brigadier-General Abel
Monday, according to today's official paper The New Light of
Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar minister explained his country's preparation for
ASEAN membership, economic development, international trade,
cooperation with economic organizations and investment.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN mission also discussed ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA)
with officials of Myanmar Trade and Customs Department, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar, holding observer status of the ASEAN, is to be
admitted into the grouping simultaneously with Cambodia and Laos
according to a decision made at the last informal ASEAN summit in
Jakarta last November without setting the time frame for the
entry.
</P>
<P>
Secretary-General of the Standing Committee of the ASEAN Ajit
Singh, who visited Myanmar last November, stressed that the ASEAN
would do its best to assist Myanmar in joining the grouping,
saying that Myanmar was almost ready for membership without
difficulty in acceding to ASEAN agreements and financial
obligations including joining AFTA since Myanmar was granting MFN
status to other countries and having better position and
advantages over other observer countries.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ASEAN foreign ministers will meet informally in
Kuala Lumpur at the end of May to decide whether the three
observer countries will be admitted into the grouping this July.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN now groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam , and its members
will be expanded to Cambodia, Laos and Myanmar after their entry.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
