<HEADLINE> Manila to Sign Pact for Former Rebels' Livelihood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government, the
Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF) and the United Nations will
sign today an agreement for development of basic services,
livelihood and job creation for former Muslim rebels and their
families.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, a big boost to the peace agreement signed last
year by the government and the MNLF, includes a funding of 28
million pesos (1 million U.S. dollars) from the United Nations
Development Program and 18 million pesos (0.6 million U.S.
dollars) for pilot emergency assistance.
</P>
<P>
Nur Misuari, MNLF chairman and governor of the Autonomous
Region in Muslim Mindanao, Director-General Cielito Habito of the
National Economic and Development Authority and UN Resident
Coordinator Sarah Timson will sign the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is expected to turn the armed MNLF rebels who can
not be absorbed by the Armed Forces of the Philippines and the
Philippine National Police into soldiers of development in their
communities.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that many MNLF members were dissatisfied with
the peace deal between the government and the MNLF and thousands
of them have defected to the Moro Islamic Liberation Front, a
rebel group that opposes the peace agreement and has sporadic
clashes with government troops.
</P>
<P>
Considering this situation, President Fidel Ramos last week
ordered all government agencies in the southern Philippines to
extend all-out support to MNLF members who can not be integrated
into the military and the police forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
