<HEADLINE> Kenya's Aguta, Ethiopia's Roba Win Boston Marathon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's runner Lameck Aguta
Monday won the 101st Boston Marathon while Ethiopia's Fatuma Roba
won the women's title.
</P>
<P>
Aguta, 25, posted a winning time of two hours 10 minutes and 34
seconds in the world's oldest annual marathon. In the past three
years, he had twice finished fourth in the race.
</P>
<P>
Olympic champion Roba, 26, won the race with a winning time of
2:26:24 in the women's division. She was never  challenged after
taking lead at the 22-mile mark.
</P>
<P>
Aguta's fellow Kenyan Joseph Kamau finished second in two hours
10 minutes and 46 seconds. Kamau was followed by Mexico's
Dionicio Ceron at 2:10:59.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's Elana Meyer finnished second in 2:27:09 in the
women's division. She was followed by her compatriot Colleen De
Reuck who posted a time of 2:28:03.
</P>
<P>
The race was participated by more than 10,400 runners from
around the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
