<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ding Song Seeks Revenge on Samsonov </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANCHESTER, England, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Ding Song,
undisputedly the best defensive table tennis player in the world,
is seeking a revenge on Belarus' Vladimir Samsonov, to whom he
has lost two important games and his reputation as a
"European-killer".
</P>
<P>
The 25-year-old Chinese, who has amused and bemused his rivals
with the unique chop-and-attack play, saw his glories and
experiences collected in the 1995 World Championships fell apart
at Samsonov's feet in their two confrontations.
</P>
<P>
Samsonov, currently world No. 4 who outlived a marathon
five-set match against Ding in the World Cup last October, handed
a second defeat to the Chinese in the Qatar Open in Feburary, the
last major event before the 44th World Championships.
</P>
<P>
"I don't care too much how far I will go in individual events
and I just hope I can meet Samsonov again and take a revenge,"
said Ding, an ace player on the Chinese men's squad bidding for
its 12th team title in the Manchester championships starting on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Ding, who helped China snatch the team title from three-time
world champion Sweden in the 1995 Worlds held in the northern
Chinese city of Tianjin, is expected to join China's five-men
lineup in the team competitions here.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese, who also ended the singles run of then world
No. 1 Jean-Michael Saive of Belgium en route to finishing fourth
in last championships, is tipped as medal hopefuls in the men's
singles, men's doubles and mixed doubles events.
</P>
<P>
Ding will pair up with three-time world championship veteran
Ma Wenge in the men's doubles and combine with 18-year-old Wang
Hui in the mixed doubles. Wang last year became the first
defensive player for a decade to win the Chinese nationals.
</P>
<P>
"I haven't lost to any Europeans other than Samsonov in recent
years," said world seventh-ranked Ding. "I'm ready for stronger
challenges here because they have been studying my style since
1995.
</P>
<P>
"But I have bad news for them: I am no longer the one in the
Tianjin championships, I am much better than that," said Ding,
who has modified traditional defensive game by adding large doses
of attacking to his play.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese can serve various spins with deceptively the same
flick of the wrist to set up killing shots. "Ding is one of the
best servers in the Chinese team," said Chinese coach Cai Zhenhua.
</P>
<P>
Ding's career is the archetypal rags to riches story. He made
the national team in 1986 and was kicked out for indiscipline in
1988, the year his father died.
</P>
<P>
Rejoining the national squad in 1991, Ding was a changed man,
a man of few words and shaking confidence which earned him a
nickname of "lonely pine" because "song" means pine in Chinese.
</P>
<P>
After two lackluster years on the Chinese team, Ding wanted to
retire in 1993. "I felt so frustrated at that time that I wanted
to end my career," Ding recalled.
</P>
<P>
Ding regained his confidence in the Swedish Open in 1994,
where he upset five world top players to win his first
international title.
</P>
<P>
"The year of 1994 was a turning point in my career," Ding said.
</P>
<P>
"Ding Song used to be a player of weak mentality and now he is
a man of lion heart," Cai said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
