<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Don't Rely on Me Too Much, Says Chinese Table Tennis Queen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANCHESTER, England, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Plagued by shoulder,
back and ankle injuries, Chinese table tennis queen Deng Yaping
warned her teammates not to rely on her too much.
</P>
<P>
"I can't promise to win two points from every team match at
the world championships," said the 24-year-old Deng. "I am
worried whether I could maintain my technical and physical form."
</P>
<P>
Deng, who has won 15 world championship and World Cup titles
and four Olympic gold medals in her 11-year-long career, is
leading a Chinese women team whose strength has been sapped by
recent retirements of top players Qiao Hong and Liu Wei.
</P>
<P>
Qiao and Liu, currently ranked second and sixth in the world,
had retired from national service to join Japanese clubs after
the Atlanta Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
Bidding for China's 12th team title in the 44th World Table
Tennis Championships is a squad of brilliant youngsters and
differing styles.
</P>
<P>
Besides fast-attacking Deng, the Chinese team has Yang Ying, a
19-year-old penholder, Li Ju, 21, a topspin player in handshake
grip, Wang Nan, a 19-year-old lefthander, Wang Chen, 22, a lanky
all-around handshaker, and Wang Hui, an 18-year-old defensive
player.
</P>
<P>
"Technically, these youngsters and I are on the equal
footing," Deng said. "What they want are stronger nerves."
</P>
<P>
Zhang Xielin agreed with his protege for eight years. "A few
youngsters may be technically better than Deng, but in terms of
mentality and experience, there is no match," he said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese coaches are worried about these youngsters' nerves to
hold pressure in the world championships.
</P>
<P>
"We have thrown international responsibilty on their
shoulders," said the Chinese women's team head coach Lu
Yuansheng. "I'm afraid it may be too heavy for them."
</P>
<P>
None of Yang (world No. 4), Li (No. 5), Wang Chen (No. 7) and
Wang Nan (No. 9), made the Olympic squad after an unimpressive
European tour early last year. Deng and three other veterans,
the same four Olympians who went to Barcelona and then completed
China's clean sweep victory in the 1995 Worlds, hit the road to
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
"One thing these young players have to bear in mind: You
aren't defending the team title here, you are fighting for it,"
Lu said.
</P>
<P>
Deng Yaping's physical condition has long been worrisome to
Chinese coaches, who know Chinese fans have got used to winning
and accept nothing less no matter what reasons.
</P>
<P>
"Deng, troubled with injuries, is no longer as strong as
before and it's the same with the Chinese team because of Qiao
and Liu's retirements," said Lu. "The Chinese team is no longer
a shoo-in at this championships.
</P>
<P>
Deng has been suffering various injuries including a lower
back problem which sometimes causes numbness in her legs.
</P>
<P>
Doctors said numbness caused by injuries was rare for table
tennis players but warned Deng's condition would deteriorate if
not treated immediately.
</P>
<P>
Deng, who wears a special belt around her waist to prevent
further injuries, had reduced her daily training time to about
three hours early this year.
</P>
<P>
"I always trained harder than the other players but this time
my physical condition doesn't allow," Deng told China Sports
Daily early April.
</P>
<P>
China's major threats in the women's team event are expected
to come from Japan, Chinese Taipei, South Korea and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Former Chinese nationals Koyama Chire and Chen Jing, playing
for Japan and Chinese Taipei, will give considerable troubles to
the defending champion team.
</P>
<P>
Chire had upset Deng Yaping in the 1994 Asian Games in
Hiroshima, Japan, while Chen had stretched the world No. 1 to
five sets in the Olympic singles final last summer.
</P>
<P>
"If Deng loses two games in team match, do you have guts to
beat strong players like Chen and Chire and win back three
points," Lu asked his young students.
</P>
<P>
"Yes, I do," answered Yang Ying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
