<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Weakened in New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar fell against the
German mark Monday as uncertainty about the launching of the
single European currency was heightened.
</P>
<P>
The mood came from French President Jacques Chirac's
dissolvement of the National Assembly and ordering early
parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
In New York, the dollar settled at 1.6978 marks, down from
1.7119 marks on Friday. The dollar cost 125.31 yen, down from
125.88 yen. The pound cost 1.6353 U.S. dollars, up from 1.6332
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The possibility of delay in the monetary union benefits the
mark, since the establishment of a single currency would eliminate
the German currency from its current dominant position in Europe.
</P>
<P>
In the past few weeks, the dollar has hit a 4-year high of
127.14 yen and a 3-year high of 1.7374 marks.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Friday:
1.4425 Swiss francs, down from 1.4560; 5.7305 French francs, down
from 5.7650; 1,691.00 Italian lira, down from 1,691.50; 1.3984
Canadian dollars, down from 1.3989.  
</P>
</TEXT>
