<HEADLINE> China Energy Resources Listed on American Stock Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The China Energy Resources
Corporation today announced the listing of its common shares on
the American Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
"We are pleased to announce the listing of our common shares on
the American Stock Exchange," said Li Hongwu, Chairman of the
Board and President of this British Virgin Islands holding company
which, through its wholly owned subsidiary, has an interest in a
mainland China-based coal refining joint venture.
</P>
<P>
Its first batch of shares being traded on the market were set
at 5,700 at an opening price of 6 U.S. dollars a share. Its
closing price was 5.75 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, China granted the Mishan City, in Heilongjiang
province, the right to operate the joint venture to mine certain
sizable coal reserves in five of the city's districts for a period
of 100 years. All of China Energy Resources' operations are
conducted through this joint venture.
</P>
<P>
"China's energy market has enormous potential," Mr. Li stated.
"Presently, China is producing approximately one billion tons of
coal per year, about 30 percent of which is used for power
generation. The State Planning Commission forecasts that by the
year 2000, annual output will be increased to approximately 1.5
billion tons, with roughly one-third used for power generation.
The substantial majority of energy in China is coal-fired thermal
power."
</P>
<P>
China Energy Resources is a British Virgin Islands holding
company which owns an 80 percent interest in Mishan Hua Xing Coke
Limited, a foreign equity joint venture company. A local Chinese
government entity owns the remaining 20 percent interest in the
Joint Venture. The term of the Joint Venture, which commenced in
October 1995, is for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
The Joint Venture has production facilities located in Mishan
City and Qitaihe City in the northeast region of China's
Heilongjiang Province. The Joint Venture produces metallurgical
coke and steam coal and is developing its capabilities to produce
foundry coke.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
