<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudanese Government Signs Peace Agreement With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, APRIL 21 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese government signed here
today a peace agreement with four small southern rebel factions in
a bid to put an end to the 13-year civil war.
</P>
<P>
However, the largest anti-government group operating in
southern Sudan, the Sudan People's Liberation Army refused to sign
the accords, creating uncertainty whether the peace can be holding.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Sudanese Vice President Al-Zubeir
Mohammed Salih, on behalf of the Sudanese government, and the
leaders of the four factions.
</P>
<P>
Among those present at the signing ceremony were Sudanese
President Omar al-Bashir, President Ange Patasse of the Central
African Republic and President of Chad Idriss Deby.
</P>
<P>
The agreement defined a four-year transition period, during
which a coordination council composed of government officials and
representatives from the four factions will take charge of affairs
in the south.
</P>
<P>
After the transition period, citizens in the south will decide
by ballot whether they will stay in or to separate from the
country.
</P>
<P>
Rebels have fought the government in Khartoum since 1983,
seeking a greater say for the south in Sudan's affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
