<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Slide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 21 (Xinhua) -- New York stocks slid today,
giving back part of last week's rally, with the Dow Jones
industrial average declining 43.34 points to 6,660.21.
</P>
<P>
The Dow bounced back from an 86-point slide over the last a few
minutes. The barometer of 30 big companies added 310 points last
week, recovering nearly half of the 700 points it lost over the
prior month.
</P>
<P>
Broader measures also turned sharply lower in the afternoon
after Alice Rivlin, vice chairman of the Federal Reserve,
heightened fears the central bank will raise interest rates
repeatedly to fight inflation.
</P>
<P>
Rivlin cautioned that persistent strength in consumer demand
could aggravate inflationary pressures at the nation's factories.
After her comments reached the market, bond prices fell, lifting
the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond to 7.09 percent from 7.06
percent of last week.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 9-to-5 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled only 393.65
million shares down from 468.17 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 5.97 to 760.37, and
the NYSE composite index fell 3.24 to 399.40.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index fell 18.35 to 1,204.22, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index fell 4.54 to 551.47.
</P>
</TEXT>
