<HEADLINE> U.S. Deficit Declines 13% in First Half of Fiscal 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 21 (Xinhua) -- In the first half of fiscal
1997, steady economic growth in the country is helping to make the
federal budget deficit 13 percent below the same period of last
year, according to a report from the Treasury Department today.
</P>
<P>
March's deficit was some 21.3 billion U.S. dollars, which
brought the deficit from October through March to 111.3 billion
dollars as compared with 127.7 billion dollars during the first
half of fiscal 1996.
</P>
<P>
For all of 1996, the deficit totaled 107 billion dollars, the
lowest figure in the past 17 years. The Clinton administration
forecast a 125.6 billion dollar deficit for all of fiscal 1997.
</P>
<P>
U.S. economic growth, by raising individuals' incomes and
corporations' profits, increases the government's tax revenue.
Individual income tax collections, at 320.4 billion dollars in the
first six months of this fiscal year, are running 9 percent higher
than that of 1996. Total revenue, at 695.1 billion dollars, is 8
percent increase over the corresponding period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, over-all spending stood at 806.4 billion dollars for
the first half of the fiscal year, which is up only 4.3 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
