<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ottawa Cedes Job Training to Quebec </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government signed
over to Quebec control of job-training programs in the province in
Montreal today.
</P>
<P>
The federal government agreed to pay Quebec 1.9 billion U.S.
dollars over the next five years to assume responsibility for
helping unemployed workers re-enter the work force.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Ottawa also will pay Quebec 190 million dollars to
cover the administrative costs of the transition.
</P>
<P>
"This agreement demonstrates that our governments can work
together to find practical solutions that are adapted to the real
problems of Quebecers," Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien said
at the signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony was also attended by Quebec Premier Lucien
Bouchard, who said that his province has been seeking more powers
in job training since 1965.
</P>
<P>
"It also demonstrates the Government of Canada's determination
to renew the federation, step by step, in an orderly fashion, and
in the interests of all Canadians," Chretien added.
</P>
<P>
Last May, Canada's federal government offered all provinces the
possibility of assuming responsibility for employment-related
services and programs, and thus adapting them to their specific
circumstances and needs.
</P>
<P>
Quebec is the fifth province to sign a manpower deal with
Ottawa after Alberta, New Brunswick, Newfoundland and Manitoba.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
