<HEADLINE> Bosnian President Criticizes Dayton Accords </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Alija Izetbegovic, chairman of
the Bosnian presidency, said on Monday that he was deeply
concerned about the slow implementation of the Dayton peace
accords.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his concerns at a meeting with representatives of
the 5-nation contact group and the Islamic countries as well as
Carl Bildt, the international community's High Representative and
presented them with an analysis of the implementation process.
</P>
<P>
The analysis, done by his aides and reported by BH Press,
listed nine areas where provisions of the peace agreement are not
implemented or being implemented slowly, such as return of
refugees, common institutions and the dispute on Brcko.
</P>
<P>
Overall, the whole peace process had a negative trend of
development until now and leads to further disintegration of
Bosnia, thus endangering the basis of peace, the analysis said.
</P>
<P>
Izetbegovic urged the Western powers which also signed the
Dayton peace agreement to fulfill their promises in helping
implementing fully the accords and use political and economic
means to punish those who obstruct the implementation process.
</P>
