<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Comet Hale-Bopp Becoming Visible in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Comet Hale-Bopp is becoming
visible in evening twilight by the end of April, the South
African Astronomical Observatory said today in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
Sharp-eyed observers could possibly spot the Comet this week,
especially in the northern part of the country, observatory
spokesman Case Rijsdijk said.
</P>
<P>
Rijsdijk said Hale-Bopp, which is definitely brighter than
Comet Halley, will appear low in the northwestern sky after
sunset.
</P>
<P>
The best viewing will be between April 25 and May 10, when the
Comet could still be reasonably bright, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970422.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Considers Still More Food Aid to DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The United States might
consider to provide still more food assistance to the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) if the United Nations World Food
Program staged another appeal to the international community, the
State Department said today.
</P>
<P>
"If the World Food Program comes forward again and say: `It's
not enough from the international community. We need more,' we
would obviously look at that very seriously," State Department
spokesman Nicholas Burns said at a regular briefing.
</P>
<P>
The United States has responded twice this year to the World
Food Program for food aid to the DPRK, and Burns said last week
that the United States will provide no more as that was what it
could have afforded.
</P>
<P>
But DPRK officials have raised the issue of food aid throughout
a series of meetings they held with U.S. and South Korean
officials in New York since last Wednesday, Burns admitted.
</P>
<P>
The New York meeting is designed to discuss the possibility of
four-party peace talks on the Korean Peninsula, proposed by U.S.
President Bill Clinton and South Korean President Kim Yong-sam.
The U.S. and South Korean officials had briefed the DPRK officials
about the proposal and are awaiting a reply from the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
Burns revised his remarks of no more food aid with regard to
the DPRK officials' request and said he could not put an end to
the story of food aid.
</P>
<P>
Again, he dismissed any links between the food aid and the New
York meeting.
</P>
<P>
"Our view is we are responding adequatedly and vigorously and
with some compassion from the humanitarian point of view to the
desperate food situation of the North Korea... but let's not link
food aid or any other issues as preconditions or conditions to the
four-party talks proposal," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
