<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Children Overlooked in E. Europe: UNICEF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The needs of millions of
vulnerable children had been overlooked by the planners of
economic reform in Central and Eastern Europe, according to the
latest report of the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF).
</P>
<P>
The report, titled Children at Risk in Central and Eastern
Europe: Perils and Promises, noted that social reform across the
region had been piecemeal and uncertain in its aims, strategies
and funding.
</P>
<P>
The report launched in Bonn today said that while too many
children were still being abandoned to state care, the public
child protection system in some countries had virtually collapsed.
</P>
<P>
Many families had to cope with a devastating deterioration
in their material conditions. Skills, social values and coping
strategies developed in the earlier decades had proved vastly
inadequate, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Poverty and social dislocation had put enormous burdens on
families who often had limited capacity of experience in taking
responsibility for children's welfare. Since child monitoring and
checking mechanisms, including those normally to be expected in
school and health systems, had been eroded and were in need of
reform, children were suffering, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The answer lay in political will to put the needs of children
high on the reform agenda, said the report covering 18 countries
in Central and Eastern Europe, the Baltic states and the
Commonwealth of Independent States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
