<HEADLINE> Bosnia Denies Summit With Serbia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Bosnian officials today denied
that chairman of the Bosnian presidency Alija Izetbegovic will
meet with Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic within a month.
</P>
<P>
Mirza Hajric, an advisor to Izetbegovic, told the local press
that the Bosnian side had not planned such a meeting with
Milosevic, but a summit with Croatian President Franjo Tudjman was
being prepared.
</P>
<P>
Quoting Bosnian Ambassador to Croatia Kasim Trnka, the Belgrade
weekly Nasa Borba reported last week that preparations for the
Izetbegovic-Milosevic summit were underway and the venue would be
somewhere in Croatia.
</P>
<P>
Trnka said that he was misquoted by the journalist of Nasa
Borba who had interviewed him, according to the Sarajevo press.
</P>
<P>
The reported summit was supposed to focus on the establishment
of diplomatic relations between Bosnia and Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The process of normalizing ties between the two countries has
been bogged down on Belgrade's requirement that Bosnia should
withdraw its lawsuit against Yugoslavia from the international
court in the Hague. The Bosnian side has insisted on unconditional
establishment of bilateral relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
