<HEADLINE> Canada's Wholesale Sees Three Percent Rise in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Across-the-board increases led to
a 3.0 percent jump in sales by Canadian wholesalers in February,
Statistics Canada reported today.
</P>
<P>
"This was the largest monthly sales increase since March 1991,
when the wholesaling industry started to come out of the
recession," the federal agency said.
</P>
<P>
Wholesale trade reached 16.6 billion U.S. dollars in February,
continuing the upward movement started in January 1996. Monthly
sales have increased by 13.8 percent over the last 12 months.
</P>
<P>
In February, Canada's wholesalers of farm machinery and
equipment were the most active, with sales rising by 16.6 percent,
followed by motor vehicles and parts (7.2 percent) and lumber and
building materials (5.0 percent).
</P>
<P>
The agricultural province of Saskatchewan recorded 6.7 percent
increase in wholesale trade, the largest gain in February. It was
followed by Alberta and British Columbia provinces, which saw 6.5
and 4.5 percent rises respectively.  
</P>
</TEXT>
