<HEADLINE> EU President Criticizes Euro-Sceptics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Jacques Santer, president of the
European Commission, the European Union (EU)'s executive body,
today lashed out at the Euro-sceptics and called for confidence
building in Europe.
</P>
<P>
He made the speech Monday in Amsterdam, where the heads of
state or government of the EU member states are scheduled in two
months time to reform the Maastricht Treaty and adopt the
Amsterdam Treaty.
</P>
<P>
"Questioning cannot be an end in itself, or be used to feed
doubt about our overall objectives. It must be transformed into
decision, determination and action," Santer said.
</P>
<P>
He believed that the EU had no choice but move on with its
integration plan. "We must act, not react -- be shapers, not
takers," he said.
</P>
<P>
The EU president expressed his disappointment with both the
media and the public debate about European integration, from which
he said he got the impression that European people themselves
"seem singularly unimpressed by" what they have achieved so far.
</P>
<P>
He criticized those who do not know "what they are talking
about," questioning if those people wanted to step backwards
towards a Europe only composed of simple trading arrangements.
</P>
<P>
"If regression is unthinkable, what other options are left? We
can stick to the status quo or move on," he said, immediately
adding that there was no such a thing as status quo since people
had to adapt themselves to changing circumstances on a daily
basis.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the younger generations needed new
motivation to move on because the initial post-war motivation for
European integration had lost its force.
</P>
<P>
The EU president believed that the prospective European single
currency Euro can act as a good example of added value, which the
EU can offer a new motivation by demonstrating.
</P>
<P>
In the speech, Santer defended the European Monetary Union
(EMU) as a factor which could boost the economic growth in Europe.
However, the Euro-sceptics have been labeling the EMU as a threat
to national monetary sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
"Inspiring confidence should also be our guiding principle for
the Intergovernmental Conference," he said, adding that the number
one priority should be getting as many of the 18 million
unemployed EU citizens back to work.
</P>
<P>
He also outlined in the speech the other two priorities which
the EU is supposed to pay close attention to -- institutional
reform and the way in which the EU comes across to its citizens.
</P>
<P>
He was worried that the EU's future enlargement would pose
another problem of efficiency, saying that the possible solution
was to widen the use of majority voting as much as possible.
</P>
<P>
Santer also called for a military capability of Europe,
explaining that the EU's credibility would be at stake if crises
at Europe's immediate borders could only be solved when the United
States threw in its weight.
</P>
<P>
"Be constructive, not destructive. That is my message for the
sceptics -- wherever in Europe," he finally said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
