<HEADLINE> African States Holds Conference on Nuclear </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The eighth conference on
cooperation in the field of nuclear sciences and technology among
the African countries began today at the Tunisian town of
Hammamat, some 70 kilometers south of the capital city of Tunis.
</P>
<P>
The five-day conference, attended by coordinators from several
African states, is co-organized by the Tunisian Nuclear Science
and Technology Center and the International Atomic Energy Agency
(IAEA).
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening session, Al Munji Safra, Tunisian
minister of scientific and technological research said that
African states should develop inter-African cooperation and work
out a sustainable development strategy, through peaceful uses of
nuclear technologies to benefit economic and social development of
the continent of Africa.
</P>
<P>
The opening session was attended by representatives of the
IAEA, the Arab Atomic Energy Authority and the Organization of
African Unity.
</P>
<P>
Participants in the conference represent Algeria, Morocco,
Libya, Egypt, South Africa, Cameroon, Cote d'Ivoire, Ethiopia,
Ghana, Kenya, Madagascar, Mali, Namibia, Niger, Nigeria, Sierra
Leone, Sudan, Zaire, Zambia, and Tunisia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
