<HEADLINE> German Beer Consumption Saw Another Drop in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Beer Consumption in Germany dropped
again in 1996, continuing a trend evident since 1992, a German
brewers' group said here today.
</P>
<P>
The German Brewery Federation said per-capita consumption of
beer in the country of 80 million fell to 131.7 liters last year
from 142 liters in 1992.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the shrinking market, the number of breweries
declined from 1,356 in 1991 to 1,234 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to the federation, people nowadays drink less and go
out to taverns less as affected by the sluggish economy. Changing
drinking habits, health concerns as well as the cold and rainy
weather in last summer had also contributed to the declined beer
consumption in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Germany's beer output last year was 114.5 million hecto-liters,
2.5 million less than in 1995, coming after the United States and
China in the world.
</P>
<P>
The country's beer exports grew by 180,000 hecto-liters to 8.55
million in 1996. An increase was meanwhile reported in imports,
which totaled 2.37 million hecto-liters, up about 500,000
hecto-liters from 1995.  
</P>
</TEXT>
