<HEADLINE> US Sends Envoy to Europe on Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. launched a new
campaign to persuade its European allies to take a tougher policy
to Iran by sending a senior official to Europe, the U.S. State
Department announced today.
</P>
<P>
Peter Tarnoff, as special adviser to Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, was asked by the secretary to lead a State
Department delegation to Europe, which left Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"This mission is to consult with our European allies on our
respective policies towards Iran," State Department spokesman
Nicholas Burns told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Tarnoff, who stepped down last Friday after four years as
undersecretary of state for political affairs, will explore
"practical steps" that can be taken towards Iran, Burns said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has been accusing Iran of supporting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Tarnoff met Monday morning in The Hague with Dutch Foreign
Minister Hans van Mierlo, representing the current European Union
presidency. And he's now gone on to Bonn for meetings with the
German government.
</P>
<P>
The envoy will then travel to Paris and London before returning
to Washington on Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and its European allies have been at loggerheads over
Iran. Washington prefers tough sanctions against Iran while the
Europeans pursue a policy of constructive dialogue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
