<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Secretary-General on Chemical Weapons Convention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Secretary-General
Kofi Annan hopes that the Convention on Chemical Weapons will
become an integral part of the web of international agreements
designed to prevent the spread of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here today, one week before the
convention enters into force on April 29 1997, the
Secretary-General said that the Chemical Weapons Convention would
contribute to international peace and security in three important
ways:
</P>
<P>
- Creating an international norm prohibiting the development,
production and acquisition of chemical weapons;
</P>
<P>
- Leading to the destruction of chemical weapon stockpiles,
thereby eliminating the threat of chemical warfare;
</P>
<P>
- Establishing very stringent verification measures.
</P>
<P>
"The great potential of the convention to contribute to
international peace and security will depend on the degree of
universality it achieves," Annan said. "I have taken every
opportunity to urge member states to ratify the treaty to ensure
that the decades of difficult negotiations will not have been in
vain."
</P>
<P>
The agreement took the international community almost 30 years
to negotiate and another five years to win the requisite number of
ratifications. As of today, the convention has 74 states parties
and 162 states signatories.
</P>
<P>
"I urgently appeal to all states to take, in this final week,
the steps they must to allow the convention to fulfill its promise
and to foster a climate that will promote further advances in arms
regulation and disarmament in the years ahead. 
</P>
</TEXT>
