<HEADLINE> French Opposition Parties Embattled for Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Lionel Jospin, first secretary of
France's opposition Socialist Party, said this evening that he is
fully embattled for the early legislative elections on May 25 and
June 1, to "make this tactical dissolution the occasion for an
act of real democracy."
</P>
<P>
Jospin accused Chirac of "precipitating" France toward "a
increased austerity treatment" and "making a step closer to hard
capitalism" by dissolving the parliament.
</P>
<P>
"In this country, unemployment has not ceased to increase and
the inequality is widening... and the meaning of the future slips
away," said Jospin in a statement made after Chirac declared the
dissolution of parliament.
</P>
<P>
He condemned the "Anglo-Saxon model" of social inequality and
said that France should seek "a Europe of the citizens" without
abandoning its own model of civilization.
</P>
<P>
"It is this project of society and this model of civilization
that I will propose to you in this (election) campaign," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The national secretary of the Communist Party, Robert Hue, said
that the dissolution of parliament has taken place because a
terrible tighting up of the social and economic policy.
</P>
<P>
"People know that the problem of unemployment crushes
everybody, and the hardships are enormous," said Hue on a
televised discussion on the decision by Chirac to dissolve the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the president of the extreme-right National Front
(FN) party Jean-Marie Le Pen said that the dissolution of the
parliament is a "real political robbery."
</P>
<P>
He accused Chirac of only giving some 20 days, "of which 11
days are holidays," to others to prepare for the legislative
elections.
</P>
<P>
But he said that the FN would present 550 to 560 candidates for
the elections and said that it would "considerably raise its
scores." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
