<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-21 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian FM: No Euro-Med Partnership Without Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 21 (Xinhua) -- European-Mediterranean partnership
can not survive when instability still endangers the
Mediterranean region, Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa warned
today.
</P>
<P>
Everybody feels the necessity of maintaining
European-Mediterranean partnership as it concentrates on regional
cooperation instead of regional disputes, Moussa told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"Such partnership, however, can not be unaffected by the
problems overshadowing the regional disputes," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Especially when one speaks about common security in the
Mediterranean, it requires stability, while stability calls for
peace and peace needs justice," Moussa added.
</P>
<P>
The European Union (EU) pursues a free trade area with its
southern neighbors and hopes to sign one day a "Charter for Peace
and Stability in the Euro-Med Region."
</P>
<P>
But Arab countries, turned away by Israel's non-compliance in
the peace process, hold deep reservations about any regional
cooperation at the moment.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on reports that the Euro-Med foreign ministers
conference in Malta ended without issuing a final statement,
Moussa said the Mideast peace process has cast dark shadows on
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"The item concerning the peace process, which affected the
final outcome of Malta talks, was a controversial one," Moussa
added, saying that negotiations are still under way in this
regard.
</P>
<P>
The two-day conference last week failed to agree on a final
declaration. Also, the participants haggled over the exact text
on peace in the Mideast and how to achieve it.
</P>
<P>
Arab delegates insisted on the denunciation of Israel while
the Europeans favored a weaker text focusing on looking forward
and making progress rather than finding faults with the past.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said the Malta ministerial conference was mainly
devoted to discuss the Barcelona process, which started in 1995
in a bid to develop security, political, economic, cultural and
social ties between the 15 EU members and 12 south Mediterranean
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
