<HEADLINE> Kohl's CDU Opposes Immigration, Dual Nationality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 21 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl's
Christian Democrats (CDU) opposes loosening control over
immigration and dual nationality, having rejected such proposals
from both ruling partner and opposition, according to a top CDU
leader today.
</P>
<P>
CDU secretary-general Peter Hintze reiterated the party's
reluctance to allow in immigrants except for ethnic Germans and
Jews from central and eastern Europe, saying after an executive
committee meeting here: "We are in agreement that dual-nationality
offers no general solutions."
</P>
<P>
CDU have rejected proposals for loosening the strict laws on
immigration and dual-nationality from its coalition partner Free
Democrats as well as opposition Greens Party.
</P>
<P>
Germany bases citizenship on blood. Children born to the over
seven million foreigners living in the country cannot obtain
German nationality automatically.
</P>
<P>
At present, the about two million Turkish nationals are the
biggest single group of foreigners in Germany. Like people from
other Mediterranean countries, they came to Germany during 1950s
and early 1970s as guest workers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
