<DOCNO> XIE19970422.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Quad" Trade Ministers to Meet in Toronto Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Ministers responsible for
international trade from the United States, Japan, the European
Union and Canada will meet in Toronto next week "to discuss key
world trade issues", the Canadian government announced today.
</P>
<P>
The Quadrilateral Trade Ministers' Meeting, known as the
"Quad", will discuss the current agenda for trade negotiations
under the World Trade Organization, regional trade initiatives,
and integrating the least developed countries into the global
trading system.
</P>
<P>
The Quad was created in 1982 as an informal forum for
discussing trade issues.
</P>
<P>
"We must keep the momentum going on in liberalizing trade and
investment," said Canadian International Trade Minister Art
Eggleton, who will chair the three-day meeting starting from April
30.
</P>
<P>
"As major trading nations, we must give leadership, as well, on
new and emerging trade issues. More open and competitive markets
encourage trade, stimulating economic growth and job creation," he
added.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky, Japanese
Minister for International Trade and Industry Shinji Sato, and Sir
Leon Brittan, Vice-President of the European Commission and
Commissioner Responsible for Commercial Policy will attend the
meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
